<HEADLINE> French Fuel Still Scarce  </HEADLINE>
By ANGELA DOLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France (AP) -- In car after car, impatient drivers smoked,
read the paper or bickered with line-jumpers Friday as they waited
to fill their tanks at the only gas station open for regular
business in France's third-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been waiting three hours,'' said Philippe Le Roi, a
salesman who has had to stop visiting clients because his car is
nearly empty.
</P>
<P>
   Five days after truckers across France began a blockade of oil
refineries and depots to protest high fuel prices, Lyon is one of
the worst-hit cities, with flights canceled and almost every drop
of gasoline reserved for emergency vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, motorists nationwide had new hope the pumps might
soon reopen when a leading truckers' union called for lifting the
blockades. But a smaller union refused to back down, and farmers,
ambulances and even tow-truck drivers continued to demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the National Federation of Agricultural
Workers, one of the largest farm unions in France, said the
government had made a promising offer and that he would ask the
union to call off its protest.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Luc Duval, head of the National Center of Young Farmers,
also said he would also ask members of his organization to end
their protest.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the government offered farmers a 30 percent
decrease in gasoline taxes for the year 2000, Guyau said after
meeting with Agriculture Minister Jean Glavany.
</P>
<P>
   ''Such steps are headed in the right direction even if we have
not abandoned the idea of the complete withdrawal of the tax in the
coming years,'' Guyau said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Monday, the protesters have drawn international attention
to the difficulties they face as world fuel prices soar. They say
France's gasoline taxes -- the second-highest in the 15-member
European Union -- aggravate the problem.
</P>
<P>
   At Lyon's Lyon-Saint-Exupery airport, 18 flights were canceled
Friday because the airport has been unable to refuel planes.
</P>
<P>
   Rental car agencies had vehicles to offer, but little gasoline.
It was nearly impossible to find a cab for hire because most of the
city's taxi drivers have joined the protest. Still other cab
drivers had no fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Some travelers arriving at the international airport were
baffled.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think the French government is very weak to allow this to
happen,'' said Gareth Bevan, a Londoner who flew in to Lyon for a
wedding, along with 17 others. ''We were very worried we wouldn't
be able to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Many French motorists have sympathized with the plight of those
whose livelihood depends on gasoline. In France, a gallon of diesel
fuel costs $2.84, nearly twice the price in the United States.
Unleaded gasoline averages $3.81 a gallon, and about 75 percent of
that is tax. Fuel prices have jumped about 40 percent in the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   On the outskirts of Lyon, farmers and truckers blockading the
Feyzin refinery have slept in their trucks for days. Still, they
managed to keep up their spirits, lunching on baguettes, jugs of
wine and freshly picked apples under a huge white party tent.
Someone brought along an enormous brown cow to keep the protesters
company.
</P>
<P>
   But the county fair atmosphere belied serious concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to have to abandon our professions if the
government doesn't do something,'' said 60-year-old Marcel Damien,
whose ancestors have been farmers for eight generations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being a farmer is difficult enough, but with fuel prices up
...'' he said, shaking his head as his voice trailed off.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Gonnet, who owns a transport company, said the protests
were forcing the government to pay attention to the fuel price
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ''Normally, 800 trucks a day take fuel out of here,'' said
Gonnet, a member of the UNOSTRA union, the one truckers' group that
has not called an end to the protests. ''Not today.''
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, Transportation Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot, Glavany
and Budget Secretary Florence Parly met with Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin on Friday afternoon to address the crisis. No details were
immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the leftist government offered to give truckers a
tax refund of 19 cents per gallon this year, followed by a 6-cent
per gallon refund next year. One of the three protesting unions
accepted the offer on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   The two others held out, however. On Friday, after an overnight
meeting with Gayssot, the largest union, the National Federation of
Road Transport, accepted the deal and called for a lifting of the
barricades.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the group, known as FNTR, was not likely to put
an immediate end to the tense situation, with 112 refineries and
depots sealed off throughout France and 160 blockades in place,
according to the National Center for Road Information.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the FNTR, in disagreement with national leaders,
kept their barricades in place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
