<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Passenger Plane Hijacked  </HEADLINE>
By JARED KOTLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A man who described himself as a leftist
guerrilla prisoner hijacked a plane carrying 21 people Friday,
later freeing his captives unharmed when the plane touched down and
left him in rebel territory, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Three guards were escorting the prisoner from Bogota to the
southwest city of Florencia when he pulled a handgun and commandeer
the plane, said police director Gen. Ernesto Gilibert.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes into the flight after a refueling stop, the
prisoner went to the bathroom, emerged with a gun and headed for
the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said it was a hijacking, that it was to obtain his freedom
and that he was a guerrilla,'' said Jose Orlando Ossa, one of the
passengers aboard the Dash 230 turboprop run by the small Colombian
carrier Aires.
</P>
<P>
   Ossa spoke to reporters late Friday at the airport in Neiva, the
southwestern provincial city where the plane refueled and to which
it returned after its brief foray into guerrilla territory.
</P>
<P>
   Ossa said the hijacker identified himself as a member of
Colombia's largest guerrilla army, the Revolutionary Armed Forces
of Colombia, or FARC.
</P>
<P>
   Once on the ground at the FARC-held airport in the southern town
of San Vicente del Caguan, Ossa said the hijacker stepped off the
plane and a uniformed FARC member came aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The FARC rebel ''asked for our forgiveness, saying that he had
no knowledge of this (the hijacking) and that we would all be able
to go free,'' Ossa added.
</P>
<P>
   Gilibert, the police chief, said the hijacker is a FARC rebel
who was serving a jail sentence in Bogota for killing a police
officer. The prisoner was being transferred from Bogota to
Florencia for a judicial proceeding, he added.
</P>
<P>
   A FARC spokesman confirmed the plane landed at the San Vicente
del Caguan airport, just south of Neiva, but denied the hijacker is
a member of the guerrilla organization.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a common criminal,'' FARC spokesman Andres Paris told
Colombia's RCN television station. ''This is not a guerrilla
action. This is not a FARC action.''
</P>
<P>
   Paris said the rebels had apprehended the hijacker, although it
was unclear whether they planned to turn him over to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The hijacking could upset fragile peace talks between the FARC
and President Andres Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
   San Vicente del Caguan is part of a a five-township southern
region that has been ceded to the FARC as part of the negotiations.
Troops and police are not allowed to enter the territory, about
twice the size of New Jersey, which military officials charge has
become a haven for criminal activities.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's hijacking was the second this year by a prisoner being
escorted on a flight by federal prison guards.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a convicted murderer being transferred from one
prison to another hijacked at knife point a flight with 17
passengers aboard. In the bizarre incident, the man forced the
plane to land in a northern region rife with right-wing
paramilitary squads and was killed hours later by the militias.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
