<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Offers Advice To Candidates  </HEADLINE>
By CLAUDE R. MARX
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The next time Rep. Ron Klink, D-Pa., airs
advertisements asking people to send him to the Senate, the unseen
hand of President Clinton will be there.
</P>
<P>
   ''He told me how to boil down issues for public consumption. On
Medicare, he told me to emphasize the impact on individuals,'' said
Klink, who is challenging first-term Republican Sen. Rick Santorum
in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   After speaking at a July reception here that netted the
four-term congressman $500,000, the president stayed at the hotel
for an extra 25 minutes to give Klink a tutorial in retail
politics, Clinton style.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Clinton gave Las Vegas lawyer Ed Bernstein a similar
lesson during a limousine ride. Bernstein, who has never sought
elective office before, is running for an open Senate seat against
former Rep. John Ensign, R-Nev.
</P>
<P>
   ''He told me 'Eddie, keep talking about the differences between
you and John Ensign. If you do that you'll win,' ''Bernstein said.
''After he gives speeches, he'll point out certain phrases he think
will be helpful in framing issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The advice has not given Bernstein the lead and the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee still does not rate the race as one
of the party's best opportunities to win.
</P>
<P>
   With no campaign of his own to worry about, Clinton has found a
new role for himself this year as political guru and strategist.
</P>
<P>
   While his top congressional priority is electing first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton to the Senate from New York, he has been
involved in races in California, Florida, Nevada and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who often edited and rewrote his own campaign ads, has
not limited himself to helping candidates craft their message. He
has tapped his knowledge of turnout trends to help candidates get
out the vote.
</P>
<P>
   He has spoken with Bill Nelson, the Democratic nominee for
Senate in Florida, about ways to encourage more Hispanics to vote,
according to the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, the state insurance commissioner, is running for an open
seat against Republican Rep. Bill McCollum. Nelson leads in the
most recent Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel poll by 11 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   The president draws on his experience in running two winning
national campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ''He remembers how he did in many areas and told me how I can do
as well,'' said Klink. ''It kind of blew me away when he went
precinct by precinct and county by county and discussed how they
voted. That's why he has been intimately involved in campaign
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   A Pittsburgh Tribune-Review poll released Friday showed Klink
trailing by 13 percentage points, but that's an improvement over
the 20 percentage-point gap in the Keystone Poll, released in July
by Millersville University.
</P>
<P>
   Klink predicts that the gap will narrow when he goes on the air
and takes some of Clinton's suggestions. He declined to discuss his
advertising strategy or timetable.
</P>
<P>
   University of Virginia political scientist Larry Sabato doubts
that Clinton's political skills are transferable.
</P>
<P>
   ''He knows politics as well or better than anyone, but his
skills are better suited for someone of his talents for others,''
Sabato said.
</P>
<P>
   Sabato, who has written several books on campaign strategy, said
that because much of the public mistrusts Clinton, candidates could
suffer if they are too closely identified with him.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he has advice to give, he should do it in the wee hours
when no one is watching,'' Sabato added.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his new avocation as a campaign consultant, Clinton
devotes lots of time to raising money for candidates. He averages
about 12 events per month.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is our most effective fund-raiser; there is no Clinton
fatigue among donors,'' said Democratic National Chairman Ed
Rendell.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein campaign: http://www.bernstein4senate.com
</P>
<P>
   Klink campaign: http://www.klinkforsenate.com
</P>
<P>
   Nelson campaign: http://www.nelsonforsenate.com	   White House:
http://www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
