<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Leader Urges Treaty Action  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD PYLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- South Korea's president has disputed reports of
growing anti-American sentiment in his country, but warned of that
possibility if the two governments don't quickly update a U.S.
armed forces agreement and deal with other military-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing a Korea Society dinner at the conclusion of the U.N.
Millennium Summit, President Kim Dae-jung said a key complaint was
the lack of progress in negotiations to revise the armed forces
pact -- called the Status of Forces Agreement, or SOFA -- to make it
equal to those with Japan and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Kim said other issues were recent claims of U.S. troops killing
a large number of civilians during the Korean War as well as a
pollution scandal involving the American military.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is frustration and criticism over the slow progress in
the work of revising the agreement, the reported killing of No Gun
Ri villagers during the Korean War and environmental pollution at
some U.S. military installations,'' Kim said.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I fear is that if the problems are left to fester, they
could be exploited by the very few who are against the United
States to expand their influence. Lest that happen, we must bring
these issues to a very prompt and convincing resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   About 37,000 American troops are stationed in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries began talks last month on updating the
1960s-era SOFA pact, a key element being a Korean demand for
immediate legal custody of American service personnel accused of
crimes. At present the U.S. command keeps custody until a
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials point out that Status of Forces pacts in
Germany and Japan give local judicial systems this right, and
consider it discriminatory that Korea's does not. The United States
traditionally resists subjecting its personnel to foreign judicial
systems that do not contain the same protections as American laws.
</P>
<P>
   Kim said he believed the call for a change in the South Korean
SOFA was ''reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is criticism and a demand, not an expression of
anti-Americanism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ''absolute majority of the Korean people'' share his
appreciation for the ''abiding friendship and support'' of the
United States, said the 74-year-old Kim, a one-time political
dissident who was imprisoned by South Korea's authoritarian
governments in the early 1980s and spent part of two years under a
death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. and South Korean governments are investigating claims,
first reported by The Associated Press last year, that Korean
civilians had been killed by U.S. troops at No Gun Ri in July 1950,
in the early days of the Korean War. Former soldiers spoke of 100,
200 or simply hundreds dead. The South Koreans say up to 300 were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   The pollution controversy stems from a U.S. base's dumping of a
formaldehyde solution into Seoul's Han river through a sewage
conduit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-09-00 0108 </TRAILER>
