<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angels 2, Orioles 1  </HEADLINE>
By KEN PETERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Ramon Ortiz pitched out of his recent
slump with 7 2-3 strong innings, and Benji Gil homered Friday night
as the Anaheim Angels downed the Baltimore Orioles 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz (5-5) held the Orioles to one run on three hits. The
rookie struck out five and walked four in winning for the first
time in six starts dating back to Aug. 8, when he beat Boston and
Pedro Martinez 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Percival pitched the ninth for his 27th in 36 chances.
</P>
<P>
   Gil's solo shot to right-center field in the sixth inning off
Pat Rapp (7-11) provided the go-ahead run. His opposite-field homer
was his sixth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Richard had drawn the Orioles even in the fifth with his
eighth homer, a one-out drive over the fence in center on a 3-1
pitch from Ortiz.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim took its first lead in the second. Bengie Molina singled
with one out and moved up on Adam Kennedy's single, his first of
three for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Molina then scored when Darin Erstad's grounder up the middle
skipped just past the outstretched glove of diving second baseman
Jerry Hairston for a single.
</P>
<P>
   After his spectacular win over Boston, Ortiz lost three of his
next six starts. He was rocked for nine runs on eight hits in his
last previous outing, although he got no decision in the Angels'
13-12 loss to the Chicago White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Holtz relieved with a runner on second and two outs in the
eighth and ended the inning by getting Brady Anderson on a pop fly.
</P>
<P>
   Rapp gave up two runs on six hits in six innings. He struck out
two, walked three and hit a batter as he lost for the fifth time in
his last seven starts.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a victory at Cleveland last Sunday, he was trying to
win consecutive starts for the first time since April.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles again were without slugger Albert Belle, who was
examined by doctors in Baltimore on Wednesday and is listed as
day-to-day with inflammation in his right hip.
</P>
<P>
   Belle has missed four games because of the injury. He is batting
just .215 in his last 39 games and has only four homers in his past
59 games.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Angels announced they have agreed to terms with RHP
Chris Bootcheck, who was the team's second pick in the first round
of the 2000 free agent draft, the 28th player taken. He had a 9-2
record and 3.76 ERA for Auburn last season. His father, Dan, played
in the Detroit Tigers' organization from 1966-73. ... When RHP Luis
Rivera makes his Orioles debut, he will be their 50th player of the
year, a club high. He also will be their 22nd pitcher of the
season, which is tied for the second most in club history. ... The
Angels' Mo Vaughn was back at first base after being the DH in the
two previous games because of a sore left ankle. He went 1-for-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
