<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democratic Concerts Aim For $7M  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Al Gore, looking ahead to a $7 million week of
fund raising with the stars, tried to stir campaign contributors
with a warning: ''The other side has pulled out all the stops.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic presidential nominee beseeched donors at a
reception Friday night to help him even the financial score with
rival George W. Bush and the Republican Party, which have raised
record amounts for this election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you could just help us remain in the same ballpark, even
close, then that's what we need,'' Gore told about 250 people who
paid $1,000 apiece to see him in an over-air-conditioned hotel
ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   All year, the Democratic National Committee has trailed the
Republican National Committee in fund raising and Bush has raised a
staggering $100 million. The GOP nominee spent a record $93 million
through the end of July -- more than double Gore's expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   ''The other side has pulled out all the stops and just gone way
beyond what anybody ever thought would happen in the post-Watergate
reform era,'' Gore said at the Atlanta reception.
</P>
<P>
   Before returning to Washington for a weekend off at home, Gore
asked contributors at a $750,000 dinner to spread the word. ''I
want you to also encourage others to get on this cause and help us
push it forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Through June 30, the GOP had $21.1 million in hard cash in the
bank, compared with $9.3 million for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, both parties have spent millions on an unusually
early and aggressive TV ad war.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will help the DNC replenish its coffers next week -- in
between campaign stops focused on education -- with a trifecta of
benefit concerts that one member of his campaign entourage has
dubbed ''Moolah-palooza.''
</P>
<P>
   Singers Cher and Michael Bolton star at Tuesday's $800,000 gig
in Philadelphia. On Wednesday, it's singer James Taylor in Boston
to raise $1 million. The Thursday finale, at New York's Radio City
Music Hall, employs the likes of Bette Midler, Jon Bon Jovi, Paul
Simon and Julia Roberts to bag the week's biggest tally -- $5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, will separately do
his part with a $1.5 million marathon of four fund raisers Monday
in Bush's Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
