<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jamaican PM Touts Anti-Crime Plan  </HEADLINE>
By IAN JAMES
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Jamaica's prime minister is seeking to reassure
business leaders and government officials that his country will
handle a rising tide of violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Friday at the Americas Society, Prime Minister P.J.
Patterson outlined his government's new plan aimed at easing
violence and stemming the flow of drugs and guns. More than 600
people have been murdered this year on the Caribbean island.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have reason to be concerned,'' Patterson said. ''We are
determined to ensure that our beautiful country is a safe place.''
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister, who visited New York this week to attend the
U.N. Millennium Summit, told an audience of about 100 people that
the centerpiece of his new anti-crime plan is ''the creation of an
elite strike force, led and manned by the best of our security
forces.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We know that freedom from fear of violence contributes
meaningfully to an environment that is conducive to investment and
higher levels of economic growth,'' Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jamaican economy has shrunk 4.2 percent since 1996, and
although unemployment is officially running at 16.3 percent, the
true figure is estimated to be between 20 percent and 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both local and foreign businesses have complained recently about
Jamaica's high crime rate. The island's leading entrepreneur,
Gordon Stewart, who owns Sandals Resorts International chain and
Air Jamaica, recently said he might leave the country if the crime
situation doesn't improve.
</P>
<P>
   During his speech, Patterson outlined what he said were economic
improvements during his tenure and said the country is seeking
investment to boost growth.
</P>
<P>
   But he also expressed concern about the increasing globalization
of the world economy, describing it as a ''brand new ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Its advent has not produced equal benefits to all the nations
of the Earth, and in several instances has so far only served to
entrench age-old interests and widen previous disparities,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other representatives of small nations expressed similar worries
in New York this week.
</P>
<P>
   Haitian President Rene Preval on Thursday spoke of ''a new
source of inequality and divisions among nations'' and warned that
a widening gap between the rich and the poor could lead to a
''social explosion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
