<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 02:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Runner Withdraws From Olympics  </HEADLINE>
By BERT ROSENTHAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) -- A recurring respiratory problem has
knocked America's top medal contender out of the women's 1,500
meters at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Jacobs said Friday she had problems breathing since
racing in a meet in Zurich, Switzerland, Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a result, I was feeling very fatigued and sluggish,''
Jacobs, 37, said in a statement released by Nike.
</P>
<P>
   While her condition appeared to be improving until Tuesday, ''I
had a relapse and couldn't even complete my workout.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had hoped to get it under control before Sydney, but we
seemed to have run out of time. Further, Tom (husband/coach Tom
Craig) and I felt that competing at Sydney could put me at risk of
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, I'm very disappointed and wish I could be competing
in Sydney. These things happen and now I just have to focus on the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said she would be in Sydney to support the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   Her agent, Emmanuel Hudson, also expressed disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was very sorry to get the call from Regina yesterday,'' he
said. ''She was a favorite for a medal and it's a very unfortunate
situation for her. It's a big loss for U.S. track and field and the
Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. women's coach Karen Dennis said a replacement had not been
picked, but the top candidate would be Shayne Culpepper, the
fourth-place finisher at the U.S. Olympic trials in July at
Sacramento, Calif. Culpepper's husband, Alan, is a member of the
10,000-meter team.
</P>
<P>
   The other members of the 1,500 team are Suzy Favor Hamilton and
Marla Runyan.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs won the 1,500 at the trials and set the U.S. record in
the 5,000 meters. She withdrew from the Olympic 5,000 to
concentrate on the 1,500, in which she won the world indoor title
in 1995 and was the world outdoor silver medalist in 1997 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   This would have been Jacobs' fourth Olympics. In 1988 and 1992,
she failed to make the 1,500 final and in 1996 she finished 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs has won the U.S. 1,500 outdoor title eight times,
including last year when she also doubled in the 1,500 and 5,000,
and was a bronze medallist in the 3,000 at the 1999 world indoor
championships.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-09-00 0218 </TRAILER>
