<HEADLINE> Vatican Aide's Book Makes Claims  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- A top aide to Pope John Paul II claims primacy for
the Roman Catholic faith in an upcoming book that says the church
hopes that Jews will embrace Christianity, a German magazine
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The book by Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, the powerful Vatican
official who oversees Roman Catholic doctrine, says ''Catholics
don't want to impose Christ on the Jews, but they are waiting for
the moment when Israel too says yes to Christ,'' according to the
Focus weekly.
</P>
<P>
   On relations with Protestant churches, Ratzinger said the goal
was to unite Christianity in a single faith with Catholics taking
the lead. ''We as Catholics are convinced that such a single church
exists in its basic form in the Catholic church,'' Focus quoted
from the book, due to be published next month.
</P>
<P>
   The reported excerpts were in line with a declaration this month
by the Vatican's Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith, headed
by Ratzinger, that questioned what it said were attempts to portray
all religions as equal.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II has made reaching out to non-Catholics a focus
of his 22-year papacy. But Ratzinger, a German, appears to be
setting limits on such attempts to improve interfaith relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
