<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three more birds, 7 mosquito more pools test positive for West Nile virus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Three more birds and seven more mosquito pools
have tested positive for the West Nile virus, a city health
official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the birds were found in Queens and a third was discovered
in the Bronx, Deputy Commissioner of Health Benjamin Mojica said at
a news conference with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. Of the mosquito
pools which tested positive, four were in Brooklyn and the rest
were in Staten Island, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the recent findings, more spraying has been
scheduled against the virus-carrying mosquitos.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Queens are scheduled to be sprayed starting at 10 p.m.
Saturday, and spraying is to be done in Queens, Brooklyn and the
Bronx on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''As the mosquito season continues, New Yorkers should continue
to take personal protection measures against mosquitos, including
wearing protective clothing, using mosquito repellent containing
DEET, and making sure that window screens fit tightly to keep
mosquitos from entering people's homes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, eight city residents have been struck by the virus.
</P>
<P>
   The elderly and those with weakened immune systems have the
greatest risk of infection. Symptoms include a fever, headaches and
body aches, although severe infections can result in encephalitis,
an inflammation of the brain, or meningitis, an inflammation of the
brain's lining and the spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, seven people in the metropolitan area died from
virus-related symptoms and scores more were hospitalized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
