<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Fuel Still Scarce  </HEADLINE>
By JOCELYN GECKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French truckers began lifting nationwide blockades
at oil refineries and fuel depots Saturday after union leaders
unanimously called for an end to a six-day protest that has
strangled fuel supplies, causing airport delays and chaos at gas
stations.
</P>
<P>
   With a majority of France's gas stations still dry, however, the
removal of blockades was not expected to ease immediately the
plight of motorists, who have had to line up bumper-to-bumper to
fill their tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Ministry said 30 oil refineries and fuel depots
were still blocked as of Saturday evening, compared with more than
100 earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   French trucker group UNOSTRA called on members Saturday to
remove blockades, saying union leaders had accepted a deal offered
by the French government to cut taxes on fuel.
</P>
<P>
   UNOSTRA, the nation's second-largest trucker group, was the last
of the three unions leading the protests to call for an end to the
action.
</P>
<P>
   ''The administration of UNOSTRA, together with myself, decided
to lift our blockades,'' union president Daniel Chevalier said. He
added that regional union leaders would immediately begin work to
disperse rank and file members from blockades around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after the National Federation of Road
Transport, the country's largest trucker union, accepted the
government's deal late Friday. A third and smaller union had
accepted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   France's leftist government offered Wednesday to give truckers a
5-cent reimbursement per liter of fuel this year, and a 3.5-cent
refund per liter on gasoline taxes next year. Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin, under pressure from Green Party members of his coalition,
vowed that no further concessions would be made.
</P>
<P>
   Since Monday, the protests by France's three main trucking
groups have drawn international attention to the difficulties they
face as world fuel prices soar. They say France's gasoline taxes --
the second-highest in the 15-member European Union -- aggravate the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Many French motorists have sympathized with the plight of those
whose livelihood depends on gasoline. One liter of diesel fuel in
France costs $2.84 per gallon, nearly twice the price of such fuel
in the United States. Fuel prices here have jumped about 40 percent
in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Truckers were joined in protests by farmers, ambulance drivers,
taxi drivers and several other groups that rely on fuel to do their
job.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture unions urged members on Friday to end their protests
after leaders emerged from late-night negotiations with Agriculture
Minister Jean Glavany saying they were satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the government offered farmers a 30 percent
decrease in gasoline taxes for the year 2000, said Luc Guyau,
president of the National Federation of Agricultural Workers, known
as FNSEA.
</P>
<P>
   Following Saturday's call to end remaining protests, truck
drivers and farmers in the Rhone region and in the north near the
France-Belgian border were among the first to clear blockades at
oil refineries and fuel depots. In the south, blockades in the
Alpes-Maritime region were also lifted.
</P>
<P>
   In the western Brittany region, however, hardline truckers
maintained protests at five fuel depots. Militant truckers have
clung to early demands for a higher tax-cut than the government
offered.
</P>
<P>
   The protest was still being felt across France, with some
airports canceling flights because of lack of fuel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
