<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some Connecticut doctors willing to assist suicide  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Some Connecticut doctors are complying with requests
by patients
to write lethal prescriptions, while many more would consider
writing deadly prescriptions if they were legalized, a study found.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The study, published in the July issue of the state medical
society journal, Connecticut Medicine, found that 83 state-licensed
doctors admitted they had written at least one lethal prescription
over their careers. Of some 160 Connecticut doctors asked by
patients to write lethal prescriptions in the preceding year, two
dozen said they complied with at least one request, the Journal
Inquirer in Manchester reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If deadly prescriptions were legalized, nearly 900 physicians
would consider writing one, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   The study was based on a survey mailed in September 1998 to
7,228 physicians licensed as of 1997 to practice in Connecticut.
Physicians were asked about medical interventions they believed
they should be permitted to perform if requested by a competent,
terminally ill patient.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 2,805 physicians who responded, 91 percent agreed that a
physician should be permitted to withhold or withdraw
life-sustaining medical treatment. More than a third agreed that a
physician should have the authority to write a prescription for
medication providing the means to end a patient's life, while a
quarter agreed with permitting a physician to administer a
medication for ending a patient's life.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the respondents said the most important
consideration in determining the appropriateness of assisted
suicide were the patient's pain, quality of life, and, to a lesser
extent, life expectancy. Nearly half said the risk of undetected
depression also was of great importance.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, more than 40 percent of the physicians
participating in the study were ''very concerned'' that
physician-assisted suicide ''might be used with certain
disadvantaged groups.''
</P>
<P>
   The study was authored by three people associated with the
Braceland Center for Mental Health and Aging at Hartford Hospital's
Institute for Living: Leslie Curry, its director; Cindy Gruman, its
associate director; and Dr. Karen Blank, a senior research
psychiatrist; and by Dr. Harold M. Schwartz, psychiatrist-in-chief
and vice president of behavorial health at Hartford Hospital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
