<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public Safety commissioner seeks to increase visibility of state police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MIDDLETOWN, Conn. (AP) - State police supervisors will be
marking their unmarked cars while heading to and from work in an
effort to curb speeding and reckless driving on Connecticut's
highways during rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   Public Safety Commissioner Arthur Spada plans to distribute
magnetic signs marked ''State Police'' to about 100 upper-level
state police supervisors. The signs will be affixed to their
unmarked Ford Crown Victoria cruisers when they drive to and from
work, Spada said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has a tranquilizing effect,'' Spada said. ''It would give
us 100 extra troopers on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Spada has said he plans to make highway safety a top priority in
his administration. He already has ordered more speed traps, told
his personal driver to pull over speeders, and said he plans to ask
the legislature for more state troopers on busy highways.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Greg Senick said he has been on his way to work in his tan
cruiser when drivers in a rush inch up behind him and flash their
brights in an effort to get past him. He said he gets out of the
way and lets them pass. They have no idea he is a state police
officer until he pulls them over.
</P>
<P>
   Senick and several other supervisors who have been testing
prototypes of the signs notice that motorists rapidly adopt good
manners when they spot the marked cruisers.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I found was, by driving at the normal speed limits,
people did not pass me or tailgate me and drove around me more
safely,'' said Senick, executive officer for field operations.
''And that is what we are trying to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Ben Pagoni, who is in charge of the sign project, said the
department will also experiment with signs that hook onto the rear
trunk. The signs have to be removable since officers take their
cars home with them and are allowed to use them off duty.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our intent is not to write tickets all day long, but to get
(drivers) to voluntarily comply,'' said Pagoni, commanding officer
of research and planning for the state police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
