<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stretch of Farmington Avenue has a Brighton Beach flair  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Just across the Hartford city line,
along a 1&AMP;frac12;-mile stretch of Farmington Avenue lies a passport to
eastern Europe: Russian is spoken as often as English, shops sell
smoked white fish and rye bread and rent Hollywood films translated
into Russian.
</P>
<P>
   Even the sign next to the entrance of Walgreen's bears the
Russian word for pharmacy, ''Apteka,'' printed in Cyrillic letters.
</P>
<P>
   It's where Israel Kaganovich says he feels at home while sitting
in the courtyard outside Alfred Plant Senior Citizens Housing, more
than 4,500 miles from his native Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the 97 units at Alfred Plant are occupied by Russian
speakers like Kaganovich, who emigrated from Kiev seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They are refugees mostly from Ukraine and Belarus who settled
here in the last decade through a Jewish Family Service of Greater
Hartford relocation program.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 12 years, JFS has resettled 1,731 individuals (or
662 families) in the greater Hartford area, with the majority
making West Hartford their first American home.
</P>
<P>
   More than 380,000 immigrants have come to America from the
former Soviet Union in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pleased with this home,'' Kaganovich, an 85-year-old
retired engineer, said in Russian.
</P>
<P>
   ''One night when I couldn't sleep, I didn't want to wake my
wife, so I came out here and there was another man in the same
predicament,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the neighbors, Kaganovich visits with his
daughter and her husband, and his wife's family, who all live
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very loving atmosphere,'' he said. ''We live here as
friends, peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, 86-year-old Charna Beyder leaves Alfred
Plant with her home aide, Ludmila Sedun. Sedun - who immigrated
from Odessa, Russia, seven years ago - takes Beyder, who came from
Ukraine around the same time, to visit her son's grave.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really like it here,'' Beyder says in Russian. ''But I am
sad,'' she weeps, ''because my son is dead. He had cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same block of Farmington Avenue, ''Globus,'' a store with
a Cyrillic sign, sells Russian language books, cassettes and
compact disks and offers video rentals of eastern European films
and other movies translated into Russian.
</P>
<P>
   ''We needed a Russian bookstore,'' said Yuri Fridkin, who opened
the business two years ago after leaving his job as an engineer at
firearms maker Colt's Manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   In the adjacent storefront, Fridkin runs Golden Rain Jewelry
Inc. where he sells, designs and repairs fine jewelry. Shelves on
the walls behind cases displaying gold bracelets and watches hold
''Matrushkas,'' the popular Russian nesting dolls.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, a Russian-speaking man goes to see Ada
Ustjanauskas, owner of Cosmos International Imported and Gourmet
Food, which now caters mostly to university students seeking
Pakistani and Arab groceries.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to trade in $4 worth of pennies but can't ask an
English-speaking clerk or bank teller.
</P>
<P>
   ''They come to me with their concerns,'' Ustjanauskas said.
</P>
<P>
   Ustjanauskas, who immigrated from Lithuania after World War II,
speaks several languages including Russian and Ukrainian. For years
she has mailed packages to the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   In the same plaza, Delicacy, offering traditional Russian,
Ukrainian and Byelorussian foods along with staples of other
European cuisines, also sells Russian-language papers.
</P>
<P>
   The owner, Lilya Ladz, was a college professor in her native
Ukraine. When she immigrated here 10 years ago, she did not speak
enough English to get a teaching job.
</P>
<P>
   ''Opening a business was easier,'' said Ladz. A Baptist, she
adds: ''We came here for religious freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Connecticut, there are pockets of Russian-speaking
immigrants who seek to preserve their traditions and culture,
though the Brighton Beach flair of Farmington Avenue is unique.
</P>
<P>
   Some who fled the communist rule of the former Soviet Union have
left their mark in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation pioneer Igor Sikorsky, considered the father of the
helicopter industry, in 1929 moved his company, which is now a a
subsidiary of United Technologies Corp., to Stratford.
</P>
<P>
   A mile-long stretch of what is now Route 9 in New Britain is
named after Ukraine's 19th-century bard Taras Shevchenko, though
the poet never visited the city.
</P>
<P>
   Calculating an estimate of the number of immigrants from the
former Soviet Union - including Jews, ethnic Russians, Ukrainians,
Belorussians and others - is difficult without a careful analysis
of each area where settlements occurred over the century.
</P>
<P>
   Yale University Russian History Prof. Paul Bushkovitch said that
between 85 to 90 percent of immigrants from the Soviet Union before
the Russian Revolution in 1917 were Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Russian Orthodox and Ukrainian Uniat
Christians, also settled in industrial cities like Bridgeport and
New Haven. Many ethnic Russians, Ukrainians and Belorussians who
survived WWII came to America from displaced persons' camps in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In one New Haven neighborhood, for example, the population of an
old synagogue resettled to Woodbridge, said Bushkovitch. There was
also a Uniat church and a Russian Orthodox church, but the
population has since moved to other areas including Stratford and
Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to break down the ethnic populations would be to
track all the synagogues and churches in those areas to determine
what groups lived where and when, said Bushkovitch.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Russians, Ukrainians and Jews were all in this sort of
area,'' said Bushkovitch. ''None of these populations were huge.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Kaganovich living in the small, tight-knit community
here seems cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a great community center,'' at Alfred Plant where he
enjoys playing cards with other residents, he said. ''We call it
Carnegie Hall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-09-00 1322 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
