<DOCNO> APW20000909.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab-Americans Criticize U.S.  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gift shop owner Anwar Mohamed of Orlando,
Fla., alleges that on a trip to Israel two years ago, he was
falsely arrested, tortured, then released without explanation.
</P>
<P>
   He still is pressing the State Department to explain why U.S.
officials did little to help him. He contends it is because he is
of Arab descent, and they do not want to ruffle relations with
Israeli allies.
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed, 28, said consular officials visited him twice during
his 40 days in a Jerusalem jail. ''I begged them,'' he said. ''I
showed them my hands swollen from torture. ... I told them I was
innocent. ... I told them I needed help.''
</P>
<P>
   He and three other Arab-Americans with similar stories are to
meet with State Department officials and about a dozen senators
this week to protest what they say is unfair treatment by the U.S.
and Israeli governments. They also are seeking the release of 10
Arab-Americans they say remain imprisoned in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Fox, a spokesman at the Israeli embassy in Washington,
said he was not familiar with the case of the four men. But, he
added, ''We have a Supreme Court ruling in Israel which forbids all
kinds of torture, and that is being strictly followed.''
</P>
<P>
   That decision, in September 1999, said the Shin Bet security
service cannot use physical force as an interrogation tool, as had
been done in questioning thousands of Palestinians detained over
the years on suspicion of anti-Israeli activities.
</P>
<P>
   Partners for Peace, a private group that monitors treatment of
Palestinian-Americans, says 16 Arab-Americans were arrested and
tortured in Israel in the past 18 months. Some were released later
without charges, the organization said, but some were sentenced to
prison without trials.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis contend arrests were for various security-related
crimes, such as spying or terrorist links, Partners for Peace
president Jerri Bird said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The State Department has a foreign service manual that details
what's to be done when an American citizen is detained in a foreign
country, and in no case -- no case that I have looked at -- have the
requirements been followed,'' Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   In Tel Aviv, U.S. Embassy spokesman Larry Schwartz said Saturday
that consular officials ''have had access to all American prisoners
in Israeli custody, and the issue of the mistreatment of American
citizens was raised by American officials at very high levels with
the Israeli government.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz added that the embassy knows of no torture cases since
the 1999 Supreme Court ruling on torture.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's World Wide Web site posts a travel
advisory to U.S. citizens that if arrested in Israel for alleged
security violations, they ''may be prevented from communicating
with lawyers, family members or consular members for lengthy
periods of time, ... subject to mistreatment during the
interrogation period, ... detained for up to six months at a time
without charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird, wife of a retired foreign service employee once posted to
Israel, has pressed the department on the Arab issue for two years
and brought Mohamed and others to the department a year ago to give
statements on their ordeals.
</P>
<P>
   She identified others coming this week as Yousif Marei, manager
of an Islamic center in Chicago; Bashir Saidi, an engineer from
Inkster, Mich.; and Mike Mansour, deputy sheriff of Albuquerque,
N.M., when he was tortured for 21 days in 1984. All, like Mohamed,
say they were visiting relatives in Israel when they were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the very minimum there should be protest, a public
statement of disapproval,'' Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department:
http://travel.state.gov/israel--occupiedterritories.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-09-00 1327 </TRAILER>
