<DOCNO> APW20000909.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Acting Hartford fire chief received improper cash payments  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - City officials say the acting fire chief
and other firefighters received improper cash payments while
overseeing out-of-town authorities during exercises at a fire
training building.
</P>
<P>
   City Manager Saundra Kee Borges ordered an internal
investigation on Friday, saying Acting Fire Chief Charles A. Teale
Sr. and other firefighters were wrong to take the money.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Teale and the others accepted $40-per-hour fees
for acting as ''burn masters'' at the multistory, concrete training
building, where fires are set for exercises. City rules prohibit
the fees from being paid directly to supervising firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Teale said he did not know the practice, which has gone on for
at least nine years, was wrong. He offered Friday to repay the
money that he and the other firefighters received, estimating the
total at thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ''They didn't think they were doing anything wrong,'' Teale
said. ''They saw it as a past practice. Their intentions were
honorable. Members wanted to help improve training in other
departments.''
</P>
<P>
   The amount of money the firefighters collected was unclear.
Officials said the violations occurred at least 20 times.
</P>
<P>
   Kee Borges said city employees are not supposed to accept
private payments.
</P>
<P>
   ''You cannot use public facilities for private gain,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kee Borges said she will not consider disciplinary action until
after the investigation is finished.
</P>
<P>
   Teale, 45, is an 18-year department veteran who was expected to
be named as the permanent fire chief.
</P>
<P>
   ''He made a mistake, but I don't think it will impact his
chances to be the permanent chief,'' Kee Borges said. ''We have to
look at the sum total of his career and the good things he has done
since he has been acting chief.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the payments surprised other city officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes he goofed, obviously,'' said Councilman Steven M. Harris,
chairman of the public safety committee and a retired fire
department captain. He said he never heard of such payments during
his time in the department.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to review the investigation, but my sense, knowing
Chief Teale, is that it wasn't something done maliciously for his
own gain,'' Harris added.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Michael P. Peters, a retired city firefighter, would not
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Teale said firefighters who took the payments did not receive
overtime or regular pay from the city during the training
exercises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
