<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Student activities on hold as district and union officials negotiate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - School and teachers' union officials
bargained over a contract Saturday as student games and practices
were canceled for the weekend following a teachers' strike.
</P>
<P>
   The school board met around 9:30 a.m. Saturday to begin the
negotiations. Four hours later, spokesman Andrew Maddigan would not
discuss details of the talks. ''But we're optimistic and hopeful we
will be able to come close to an agreement this weekend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The strike took place Thursday, and was called less than an hour
before the start of school, forcing the cancellation of what would
have been the second day of classes for 47,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of children and their parents were already headed to
school and work and parents were left scrambling to find child
care.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's 3,800 teachers reported to class Friday after union
leaders asked them to show a ''sign of good will'' following a
pre-dawn meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But Superintendent Marion Canedo had already told students to
stay home because of uncertainty over the teachers' plans, so
teachers spent the day cleaning classrooms and developing lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday afternoon, Buffalo Teachers Federation president
Philip Rumore told reporters that state mediator Adam Kaufman, from
the Public Employment Relations Board, had directed the sides to
bargain around-the-clock and to refrain from speaking to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Maddigan said Friday that the talks had shifted from each side
submitting a new offer to be digested by the other side. Instead,
the ''subtle nuances'' of some of the key issues are being
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Rumore has said that teachers would not bend on their demand for
pay raises of 3.5 percent in four out of five years.
</P>
<P>
   The district's latest offer reported Friday contained
across-the-board yearly raises of 2 percent in three out of four
years.
</P>
<P>
   The strike violates the state's Taylor Law which forbids public
employees from striking. Teachers could face fines of two days' pay
for every day off the job.
</P>
<P>
   The union also face additional penalties for violating an order
issued Wednesday by state Supreme Court Justice Kevin Dillon
barring the union and four of its officers from engaging in a
strike or other illegal job actions.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers' latest contract expired in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   If school is to be closed again Monday, the district will let
parents know today, Maddigan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
