<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian TV Network Cancels Broadcast  </HEADLINE>
By JIM HEINTZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Tensions over the battle for control of Russia's
only nationwide television network escalated Saturday as the
network canceled the broadcast of its influential and controversial
political commentator Sergei Dorenko.
</P>
<P>
   The ORT network, whose initials stand for ''Public Russian
Television,'' has been gripped over the past week in a feud between
tycoon Boris Berezovsky, who controls 49 percent of ORT's shares,
and the Kremlin, which owns the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky, who is believed to exert considerable influence over
ORT's programming, has been increasingly in conflict with President
Vladimir Putin's government in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   He accuses the Russian government of trying to pressure him into
surrendering his holdings in ORT and says government officials were
moving against him and threatening possible reprisals because of
critical coverage of the government in his media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he announced he would transfer control over the
shares to 14 people, mainly journalists including Dorenko, in what
he said was an attempt to keep the shares out of government hands.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement reported by Russian news agencies, ORT general
director Konstantin Ernst said he ordered the Saturday broadcast of
Dorenko's weekly program off the air.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the increasingly complex situation, I made the request to
anchor Sergei Dorenko to refrain from commentary in today's edition
of his program on the theme of the conflict between the state and
private shareholders ... Sergei Leonidovich did not agree with
me,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Interfax news agency quoted Dorenko as saying that
''there was no kind of appeal to me from the side of Konstantin
Ernst regarding my program.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I connect the decision to take my program off the air
exclusively with Vladimir Putin,'' he was quoted as saying. It was
unclear when broadcasts of the program would resume.
</P>
<P>
   ORT once had given blanket, favorable coverage to Putin.
Dorenko's program was seen as a major contributor to the collapse
of the presidential ambitions of former Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov, whom many had seen as potentially Putin's strongest
challenger, and Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   However, Berezovsky apparently has lost the insider influence in
the Kremlin that he cultivated under former President Boris Yeltsin
and he has become increasingly critical of Putin. He resigned his
seat in the lower house of parliament, saying he was protesting
what he called Putin's attempt to impose authoritarian rule.
</P>
<P>
   Many critics allege that Putin is cracking down on press
freedoms. The issue got much attention this summer when tycoon
Vladimir Gusinsky, whose media holdings have reported critically on
the Kremlin, was jailed on charges of defrauding the state --
charges that later were dropped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
