<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Barak Meet in New York  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- With Mideast peace talks deadlocked, President
Clinton and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak met Saturday to
discuss whether the negotiations can be salvaged.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just kind of a friendly meeting,'' Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   The president gave a thumbs-up sign but did not comment when
reporters shouted to him about the meeting, which lasted about an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Both U.S. Israeli officials played down the meeting's
significance.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was really informal. ... It was not terribly substantive,''
said White House deputy press secretary Jake Siewert, adding that
Clinton wanted to say goodbye to Barak. Both leaders had come to
New York for the U.N. Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, a senior Israeli official said he had low expectations
of reaching a deal with the Palestinians in the coming weeks and
did not believe that Clinton was bringing new proposals to Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton went to Barak's hotel on Central Park for the midmorning
meeting, in deference to the Jewish Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   Barak on Friday summed up peace efforts with the Palestinians in
two words Friday: ''No good.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak told The Associated Press he made a last-ditch approach to
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat before Arafat left for Gaza, and
urged him to reach an accord in the little time remaining before
next week's self-imposed deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat was not responsive, Barak said with evident
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations are hung up mostly over Jerusalem. Arafat is
unyielding in his demand for sovereignty over the eastern part of
the city and has resisted compromises offered by Clinton and
pleadings by Barak that the Palestinian was missing an opportunity
to gain statehood.
</P>
<P>
   In Gaza City, the Palestine Liberation Organization's Central
Council was to meet Saturday to consider whether to move forward
with a unilateral declaration of statehood Wednesday as Arafat has
indicated he would do absent an overall settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and other U.S. officials
have cautioned Arafat they would not support such a state.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday is the deadline that Barak and Arafat set last year
for overall agreement. White House spokesman Joe Lockhart has
called that deadline ''artificial'' and says Clinton is prepared to
keep working past it for an accord.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Associated Press Writer Karin Laub contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
