<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Assembly fixture faces stiff opposition in primary  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Crystal Peoples rides her ''Peoples
Express'' bus through Buffalo's neediest neighborhoods with the
hope it will eventually take her to Albany, straight to the state
Assembly seat now occupied by Arthur Eve.
</P>
<P>
   After 34 years, Eve has no intention of giving up that seat.
</P>
<P>
   And so the candidates - she the majority leader of the Erie
County Legislature, he the deputy speaker of the Assembly and its
longest-serving member - do battle in the streets for the right to
represent this piece of New York virtually untouched by the
economic prosperity evident elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Eve is one of several legislative veterans facing
harder-than-usual challenges in Tuesday's primary prelude to
November's elections. Other well-known names also campaigning hard
to beat back intraparty challengers include Democratic Assemblymen
Clarence Norman and Roger Green, both of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's three-way Democratic primary in the 141st Assembly
District, Eve points proudly to his 17 terms and the housing,
education and affirmative action programs he has helped deliver to
the largely African-American district.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're running on a record which our opponent cannot run on,''
he said. ''Seniority is very important. And I'm part of the
leadership in Albany, that's very important. We've been very
effective in delivering for the city and for the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no argument over Eve's record from Peoples. After
coming of age during the civil rights movement, his social agenda
was right on target, she says. But times have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is no disrespect to the gentleman,'' Peoples, 48, said.
''It's just that ideas get old and sometimes they need to be
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The agenda that Mr. Eve has concentrated on for the last 34
years has been one that's based on social needs,'' she said, ''and
I think that was appropriate for the '60s and '70s and maybe even
the early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I think at some point we should have switched that to an
economic agenda,'' she said, ''one that focused on creating wealth,
creating access to jobs and creating opportunities to create
business.''
</P>
<P>
   High-level Democrats have been lining up behind the 67-year-old
Eve, including Buffalo Mayor Anthony Masiello, Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver, Ways and Means Committee Chairman Herman Farrell of
Manhattan and Assemblyman Paul Tokasz of Cheektowaga.
</P>
<P>
   Absent big-name supporters, Peoples, who has been in the county
Legislature for five years, is campaigning vigorously in the
streets, delivering her message one-on-one to voters.
</P>
<P>
   While Eve, too, has campaigned door-to-door, he also has taken
to the airwaves with his first television ads since taking office.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no better way to communicate 34 years of
accomplishment than through television. It's just the most
effective media,'' explained Eric Eve, a Democratic strategist who
is running his father's campaign. ''And Buffalo's media market is
one of the least expensive in the country. It didn't make sense not
to.''
</P>
<P>
   While Eve has been endorsed by the city's largest newspaper, The
Buffalo News, Peoples gained momentum in the black community with
an endorsement by the Challenger, an influential newspaper Eve
helped establish 37 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Peoples lost by a wide margin to Republican Jack Quinn
in a bid for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Herbert is the third Democrat in the Assembly race.
</P>
<P>
   In other competitive primary contests Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   -In Manhattan, Democrats in the 68th Assembly District will
choose between incumbent Nelson Antonio Denis, Adam Clayton Powell
4th and two other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Denis is seeking his third term in the Assembly while the
38-year-old Powell, the son of the former Harlem congressman, is
seeking to get back into politics for the first time since 1997.
That year, Powell resigned his seat on the New York City Council
and ran unsuccessfully for Manhattan borough president.
</P>
<P>
   -Former state Sen. Pedro Espada Jr. is in a rematch with the
Democrat who took his job in 1996 in the Senate's 32nd District,
David Rosado. Rosado beat Espada by 745 votes in the 1998
Democratic primary. The district is in the South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   -Norman is one of the more influential members of the Assembly,
both because of his nine terms of tenure and his position as
Brooklyn's Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   But he won by only 677 votes in a 1998 primary against James E.
Davis, and Davis is challenging Norman again this year for the
Democratic nomination in the 43rd Assembly district.
</P>
<P>
   Norman says he was distracted by other races last time and is
focusing on his own primary this time. Davis is a police officer
and a minister.
</P>
<P>
   -In the 57th Assembly District in Brooklyn, incumbent Democrat
Green was campaigning hard in his contest against Hakeem Jeffries.
</P>
<P>
   -In the 127th Assembly District, in the state's Finger Lakes
region, incumbent Republican George Winner was facing a primary
rematch - from 1978. Chemung County legislator Sidney Graubard has
been the only Republican to challenge Winner, who serves as the
floor leader of the Republican minority in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   -On Staten Island, borough Democratic leader John Lavelle is
being opposed by a Democratic district leader for the 59th Assembly
District seat being given up this year by the retiring Democrat
Elizabeth Connelly.
</P>
<P>
   -In Buffalo, incumbent Assemblyman Sam Hoyt, who first backed
former Majority Leader Michael Bragman's coup attempt against
Silver and then switched back to Silver's side, is being challenged
by Antoinette Guercio.
</P>
<P>
   -State Sen. Alfred Coppola is being challenged by Byron Brown, a
veteran of the Buffalo Common Council in the Senate's 57th
District. Brown has previously held staff positions in the Erie
County Legislature and the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press Writer Joel Stashenko contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-09-00 1401 </TRAILER>
