<DOCNO> APW20000909.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio faces complaints that he may be too laid-back  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton's Republican opponent
in New York's U.S. Senate race, Rep. Rick Lazio, is under pressure
from top-level supporters to buckle down after a summer in which he
came across to some as a bit too laid back.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did say to him, 'Look, I really think you've got to pick up
the pace a little bit,''' said Michael Long, chairman of the
state's small, but politically important Conservative Party which
has endorsed Lazio. ''He said he had no problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar advice on stepping up campaign efforts has come from
Republican Gov. George Pataki, according to GOP sources.
</P>
<P>
   Long's heart-to-heart with Lazio came as the congressman joined
the party leader at a Queens beach club last Sunday to shake hands
with some potential voters, ending a four-day, pre-Labor Day family
vacation in the posh Hamptons on the east end of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the vacation, a fund-raising letter from the
congressman had surfaced in which he made a pointed plea to
potential donors.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we are to reach every possible voter, I need to concentrate
my personal efforts on campaigning rather than fund raising. I must
attend rallies, shake hands with voters and make speeches to as
many groups as possible,'' the congressman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Lazio headed off on vacation, not to be spotted on
the campaign trail again until five days later when he showed up at
the beach club with Long.
</P>
<P>
   After that Lazio paid a Labor Day visit to the State Fair in
Syracuse and began a full schedule that saw appearances around the
state and out-of-state fund-raisers before heading to Washington
for congressional business. His aides have said all along that the
plan was to hit the campaign trail hard after Labor Day and
Republican leaders are hoping the pace keeps up.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also taken what were billed as vacations this summer
with her husband, sometimes joined by daughter Chelsea. But they
have been more like working vacations with well publicized
fund-raisers and public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at the State Fair in Syracuse if it felt like being on
vacation, the first lady raised her eyebrows and said: ''Sort of.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lazio was taking it too easy, it was left to Long to deliver
the message.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was with him Sunday campaigning and I thought he did very
well,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio and his aides say the candidate has been busy raising
money, putting together a staff and doing all the other things
needed to get a campaign up and running.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's in pretty good shape - not pretty good - I think
he's in good shape considering he's been at this around 91 or 92
days, not a year and a half like she has been,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He planted his trees. The trouble is he's got to get his trees
to grow faster than hers ... The biggest factor is that he didn't
have time to develop what you would call deep roots,'' the party
leader said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio campaign manager Bill Dal Col said the four-day Lazio
vacation wasn't really just vacation, given that the congressman
and first lady have their first debate coming up on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''He spent two of those days in full debate prep and the other
two days with his family,'' said Dal Col, who ran millionaire
publisher Steve Forbes two unsuccessful bids for the GOP
presidential nomination. ''Believe me, with the time he's had on
the road and back in Congress voting, I am never going to begrudge
him any time with his family.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Every campaign is different,'' Pataki said when asked about
Lazio's work ethic. ''There's a big difference between public
appearances and public schedule and whether or not you're actually
working on the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got a good campaign team,'' said Pataki, who has lent
some of his own aides to the Lazio campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his late start, and complaints about his diligence,
Lazio has been running almost even with the first lady in most
statewide polls. Also, during July and August, he collected $10.8
million to her $3.3 million. Entering the final two months of the
campaign, he had $10.2 million on hand to her $7.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The value of that fund-raising work can't be overestimated, Dal
Col said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you don't have the resources to take on the onslaught that
she's put together, we'd get buried,'' the Lazio adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lazio: http://www.lazio.com
</P>
