<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former prison sergeant who claimed sex harassment awarded $150,000  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - A tearful federal jury said the state
should pay $150,000 to a female prison guard who said co-workers
and supervisors sexually harassed her for four years.
</P>
<P>
   The decision against the Department of Correctional Services
followed a one-month trial in U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Georgiann Alfano, 46, of Utica, worked as a sergeant at
Mid-State Correctional Facility in Marcy, Oneida County, for six
years, until she was fired in 1994 over allegations that she
mishandled an inmate. She claims the criticisms against her were
merely retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   The award was to compensate Alfano for mental anguish and
emotional distress, said her lawyer, Michael Sciotti.
</P>
<P>
   Sciotti said five of the seven jurors were crying when they read
the verdict around 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Alfano claimed she was sexually harassed repeatedly from 1990 to
1994.
</P>
<P>
   She said supervisors accused her of simulating oral sex with a
carrot. After that, she testified, a captain barred her from eating
carrots, bananas or hot dogs at work.
</P>
<P>
   Another sergeant testified that other lieutenants and captains
laughed about the incident and that he saw jokes and derogatory
remarks about Alfano posted at the prison.
</P>
<P>
   Alfano now owns a manicuring business in Utica.
</P>
<P>
   Correctional Services' office could not be reached for comment
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-09-00 1441 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000909.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Director Frears Honored  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Stephen Frears was a natural choice when Toronto
International Film Festival planners decided they wanted to honor a
filmmaker for the event's 25th anniversary. The trouble was
convincing Frears to agree.
</P>
<P>
   Frears, a British television director whose career swung upward
after ''My Beautiful Laundrette'' proved a hit at the festival in
1985, was gun-shy about the attention and felt such tributes tend
to signal the end of a film career.
</P>
<P>
   When festival planners first contacted Frears, his reaction was
''one of horror,'' he said Saturday in an interview before the
tribute. ''People ask to do retrospectives and you think, oh, I
see, I'm virtually dead, and I always think I don't feel I've even
started.''
</P>
<P>
   Frears has had a far-ranging career that includes the unusual
horror flick ''Mary Reilly,'' the modern western ''The Hi-Lo
Country,'' a new take on film noir with ''The Grifters'' and the
costume epic ''Dangerous Liaisons.'' The latter two grabbed
multiple Oscar nominations.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the festival did a tribute was for Warren Beatty
in 1984. Since it was the 25th anniversary for the Toronto fest,
North America's top movie showcase, organizers decided to pay
respects to a filmmaker who had a long and successful relationship
with the event.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to honor someone who's not at the end of their
career but someone in the middle, who's got films ahead of him,''
said festival director Piers Handling. ''It helped that he had a
really great this year, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Frears' work this year included the hit ''High Fidelity,''
starring John Cusack, the live TV remake of ''Fail Safe,'' with
George Clooney, and his latest film ''Liam,'' the story of
working-class Irish immigrants in Liverpool in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm on a good roll,'' Frears said. ''It's been a good
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Those three films kind of sum up how wide his career has
been,'' Handling said. ''A BBC drama, an experiment in live TV and
a contemporary American slacker film.''
</P>
<P>
   Frears made ''My Beautiful Laundrette'' for British television,
never figuring it had potential for a theatrical release. The movie
was a sharp commentary on racial tensions and economics in Margaret
Thatcher's Britain, centering on a homosexual relationship between
a Pakistani laundry operator and the white punk buddy he hires to
help out.
</P>
<P>
   ''Would you think it had theatrical possibilities? It's about a
gay, Pakistani laundrette owner,'' Frears said.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie was acquired at the Toronto festival for
theatrical release and became an arthouse hit. That led Frears into
bigger budget films and ultimately to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I started making films for television, I never
particularly wanted to be a cinema director,'' Frears said. ''I
certainly never thought I'd get to America. I never thought I'd get
to Hollywood. It was just inconceivable. It was as if someone said,
do you want to go to the moon?''
</P>
<P>
   ''Liam'' is screening at this year's festival, along with a
retrospective of Frears' movies that includes ''Dangerous
Liaisons,'' ''The Grifters,'' ''Sammy and Rosie Get Laid'' and
''The Hit,'' his first film to play at Toronto, back in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's lineup for the Frears tribute included Cusack, John
Hurt, who starred in ''The Hit,'' Jack Black from ''High Fidelity''
and Roddy Doyle, whose Dublin novels ''The Snapper'' and ''The
Van'' were adapted for film by Frears.
</P>
<P>
   Frears said it was a nice homecoming to revisit Toronto because
of the positive reaction audiences there have given his films.
</P>
<P>
   ''I remember being told that some critic in Toronto had written
the nicest thing anyone's ever said about a film of mine,'' for
''Dangerous Liaisons,'' Frears said. ''That it was like eating
chocolate in bed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-09-00 1442 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000909.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Businesses, towns still struggling to rebuild after devastating floods </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOUND BROOK, N.J. (AP) - Jim D'Agostino sits in one of the
fluorescent-green booths he had put back in a deli that Raritan
River floodwaters destroyed and remembers what it looked like a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''We went ceiling to floor,'' he said. ''We were gone.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be one year on Sept. 16 since the remnants of Hurricane
Floyd dumped historic rainfall on this town, sending the Raritan 20
feet above flood stage in the middle of a drought, filling homes to
their top floors.
</P>
<P>
   The floods killed four people around the state, including an
elderly mother and her son who refused to be evacuated from their
ground-floor apartment in Bound Brook. Damages have been estimated
at close to $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, towns say they are still waiting on money from the
federal government, the state has not distributed nearly half of a
$50 million flood relief package, and a flood control project
planned for decades in Bound Brook and more than a dozen other
towns has not yet begun.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials say their flood preparedness has changed.
New computer software installed in every county shows people when
they need to evacuate, they say. Officials talk daily with the
National Weather Service during hurricane season and monitor the
rivers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all watch,'' says Joe Painting, chief of operational
planning for the state Office of Emergency Management. ''We all
lean forward in the foxhole here from the first of June to the 30th
of November.''
</P>
<P>
   In hardest-hit Bound Brook, D'Agostino spent more than $125,000
to make his business successful again, but he doesn't think Bound
Brook has come back with him. He looks out his window to see empty
storefronts, crumbling sidewalks and holes where lampposts once
stood on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   He is more concerned about the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers'
$331 million flood control plan, which is to begin this fall by
raising a bridge in Bound Brook and setting up floodwalls and
levees. He says it won't prevent another flood because it doesn't
involve river dredging.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to get water again,'' he says. ''It's a matter of
when and how much.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the street, Phyllis Pournaras lights a cigarette in the
restaurant she owns and says the flood control project will change
this town.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once that begins, forget it,'' said Pournaras. ''This will be
prime, prime property.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bound Brook initially lost nearly half its business
district when flooded merchants decided not to return, new stores
are slowly taking their place. An eclectic cafe has taken over the
space occupied by the former Palmyra Tea room. A Chinese
restaurant, a furniture store and a barber shop have moved in.
</P>
<P>
   One recent morning, Michael Jones had several people waiting in
line for haircuts at his new shop, Mirror Image, which he opened
here because space was cheap and available.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wasn't really worried about the flood factor,'' Jones said.
He said his inventory can easily be moved in case heavy rains
threaten.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Biniek, who owns a shoe store he spent $175,000 to repair,
says his business is up 25 percent, largely because of publicity he
received from the flood.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been on Channel 12 10 times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Carzis, one of the biggest landlords in town, has spent
from $750,000 to $1 million buying up properties vacated by timid
business owners ''selling at, I think, irrational prices.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he's rented out the properties at a 40 percent to 50
percent profit.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anyone who can count should be investing in Bound Brook,''
Carzis said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents, businesspeople and government officials are strongly
at odds over Bound Brook's future. The city and a developer are
pushing a redevelopment plan that could bring a new train station,
a hotel-conference center and perhaps a satellite campus into town.
Mayor Frank Ryan says the city needs new businesses to stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   ''Forty percent of my stores are not back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A part of the plan, however, gives the city the right to condemn
homes that lie in the redevelopment zone if the homes can't be
sold. Residents who had just spent everything to restore their
homes balked.
</P>
<P>
   ''They need to clean out that river. They don't need to tear
down these houses,'' said resident Saul Valencia. ''For what? To
build an office building nobody's going to use?''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said nothing is decided - or likely will be for several
years.
</P>
<P>
   D'Agostino said overdevelopment in Bound Brook and surrounding
towns such as Bridgewater is what brought on the flooding in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   ''That river is not made to hold the runoff we're expecting it
to take,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Army Corps of Engineers will start taking bids on the first
of the flood control initiatives in Bound Brook next week,
beginning a decade-long project that is expected to protect three
counties and 14 towns from heavy flooding for at least a century.
</P>
<P>
   The state gave approval to the project three months before the
Floyd flooding. Officials said it took time to secure congressional
funding and local and county approvals.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, confusion reigns about the availability of flood aid
and how much has been received. The Federal Emergency Management
Agency says it has given out $82.4 million statewide, although
government officials say it could take years to properly account
for it.
</P>
<P>
   Bergen County hasn't received $1.4 million of the $1.7 million
it asked for from FEMA, said spokesman Thom Ammirato, who
acknowledged the problem may be about paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last year, the Legislature passed a flood relief
package that included $50 million to offer relief to residents,
businesses and counties. Just $26.2 million of that money has been
distributed, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Human Services has given out $16.2
million of $20 million set aside for resident relief, to 6,001 New
Jerseyans who applied for aid, spokesman Ed Rogan said. The state
needed to extend its deadline several times and was still unable to
distribute all the money, although Rogan said 125 applications are
still being evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   An additional $10 million for hazard mitigation has not yet been
distributed because it addresses long-term prevention needs, said
Painting of the Office of Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Community Affairs has distributed half of its
$20 million set aside for counties to distribute as they wished,
spokesman E.J. Miranda said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency initially awarded amounts ranging from $500,000 to $4
million for nine counties declared federal disasters, he said. It
then only distributed half of that amount to all the counties,
telling them they could come back for more if they needed it. Only
Somerset County came back for its full $4 million, Miranda said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We definitely want it,'' said Ammirato of Bergen County, which
had been awarded $4 million but collected $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ammirato said the county will double the grants it already gave
to about 76 businesses that applied for it, then give out checks to
the Lodi Boys Club and Felician College in Lodi, where floods
destroyed the university library.
</P>
<P>
   In Bound Brook, Pournaras stood in front of the sign outside her
Bill's II restaurant and pointed to the waterline that covers the
words ''Home Cooking'' on a sign halfway up her restaurant. She has
not touched it. She is thinking about buying a building in town and
says she is better prepared for the waters that may come.
</P>
<P>
   ''This time,'' she said, ''I have flood insurance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
