<HEADLINE> Unions Urge Strike Support at Emmys  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN ELBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Gold ribbons will be the big fashion
accessory at Sunday's Emmy Awards if striking commercial actors get
their wish.
</P>
<P>
   The Screen Actors Guild and American Federation of Television
and Radio Artists, which began a walkout May 1 against the
advertising industry, urged Emmy participants to don the ribbons in
a show of support.
</P>
<P>
   Stars joined in the call to action for colleagues who toil in
anonymity in radio and TV commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ''People tend to have the attitude that actors are buying second
homes in Malibu and living the high life, but the great majority of
actors ... are just trying to make the house payment and put the
kids through school like everyone else,'' said Jane Kaczmarek, an
Emmy nominee for ''Malcolm in the Middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaczmarek and three other Emmy contenders -- Martin Sheen of
''The West Wing,'' Tyne Daly of ''Judging Amy'' and Jerry Orbach of
''Law &AMP; Order'' -- sent out an Aug. 28 letter asking fellow nominees
to wear ribbons and publicly express support for the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the awards show takes place three days before
negotiators for the unions and the ad industry meet in New York,
the actors said the Emmys provide ''a tremendous opportunity to
demonstrate union solidarity at this critical point.''
</P>
<P>
   SAG and AFTRA want to protect residuals, or fees paid each time
a radio or television commercial is broadcast on a major network.
Advertisers want to replace residuals with flat-fee payments.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising industry representatives were unavailable for
comment Saturday. The American Association of Advertising Agencies
has held its ground, contending the industry's offer is fair and
broad and will restructure a contract that is based on outdated pay
methodology. The offer provides a substantial increase for most SAG
and AFTRA members, the association says.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of gold ribbons have been sent by the unions to actors
and their agents.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope everyone in the auditorium wears a ribbon,'' David
Hyde Pierce of ''Frasier'' said. ''With this strike in its fifth
excruciating month, it really is time for it to end.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBC sitcom's cast also asked ABC, which is airing the Emmy
ceremony, to withhold commercials featuring non-union performers
during the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ABC declined to ban non-union ads, saying the dispute was
between the unions and advertising agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Actor-comedian Garry Shandling is the host of the 52nd Annual
Primetime Emmy Awards, which features a duel between the White
House and a fictitious New Jersey crime family.
</P>
<P>
   ''The West Wing,'' the NBC series set in the White House, and
HBO's ''The Sopranos'' are competing in six categories, including
best drama and best actor (Sheen for ''The West Wing,'' James
Gandolfini for ''The Sopranos'').
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Emmys: http://abc.go.com/primetime/emmys/emmys--home.html
</P>
<P>
   SAG: http://www.sag.org
</P>
<P>
   AFTRA: http://www.aftra.org
</P>
<P>
   American Association of Advertising Agencies:
http://www.aaaa.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
