<HEADLINE> U.S. Mum on Russia Military Cutback  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The United States said Saturday it views a major
reduction in the size of Russia's military force as another among a
long series of domestic and economic reforms President Vladimir
Putin promised.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the cutback Friday to 850,000 troops from 1.2
million, Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said in Moscow the military
was ''preparing suggestions for the president on how to carry it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a decision for Russia to make, but it is certainly
consistent with what we have done with our military in the
post-Cold War era,'' White House spokesman P.J. Crowley said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is something that President Putin has indicated
previously was going to be one of his priorities. It's their
decision. It's not for us to say good, bad or indifferent.''
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, the cutback was seen as an implicit admission that
the resources-strapped government no longer can afford the size of
military organization that during the Soviet era led the Warsaw
Pact against NATO's trans-Atlantic force.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's been a debate in Russia about the size of their
military and the available resources,'' Crowley said. ''This
(cutback) would be consistent with other steps they are taking with
regard to domestic and economic reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States still maintains a worldwide force of roughly
1.4 million troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
