<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton blasts opponent's labor record; Lazio says he's proud of it. </HEADLINE>
By JUDIE GLAVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Democratic Senate candidate Hillary Rodham
Clinton criticized Republican Rep. Rick Lazio's record on labor
issues before marching in the city's belated Labor Day parade on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was not at the parade, although Grand Marshal Edward
Malloy - president of the New York Building &AMP; Construction Trades
Council - said he had been invited by a local affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio insisted Malloy was wrong. ''We did not get any
invitation.''
</P>
<P>
   At a pre-parade breakfast, Clinton said Lazio had a poor record
of voting on pro-labor and pro-family issues. Quoting an AFL-CIO
rating, she said Lazio's lifelong pro-labor voting record was 33
percent and that ''last year he outdid himself'' with only a 25
percent rating.
</P>
<P>
   ''He keeps telling people they should vote for him because of
where he was born, where he grew up, where he clammed, where he
went to school,'' Clinton said, as the friendly crowd hooted in
approval. ''Well, apparently he didn't learn very much about the
history and tradition of the progressive labor movement in his
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio disputed the charges, saying, ''I have a good labor
record.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I've voted for the Family and Medical Leave (Act) in my first
term in office. I voted for a ban on striker replacements. I voted
for prevailing wage and I've been a strong supporter of ensuring
that New York has gotten its fair share on transportation
formulas,'' he said. ''In construction, we put thousands of Long
Islanders back to work on projects that I delivered back for the
district, so I'm proud of my labor record.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton marched in the Fifth Avenue parade - which could
probably win hands down honors for being the quietest in the city.
She was neither booed nor cheered but received several shouts of
''Yeah, Hillary,'' and some polite applause along the 25-block
route.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Day parade has traditionally been a showcase for
political wannabes looking for exposure. It was not surprising that
most Republicans were missing since the New York City Central Labor
Council, the local AFL-CIO affiliate, has already endorsed Clinton
for the U.S. Senate and the Al Gore/Joe Lieberman ticket for
president.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton campaigned in Manhattan, Lazio spent the day
greeting Queens shoppers in Howard Beach and attending a park fair
in the Richmond Hill section where he was endorsed by maverick
Democratic Assemblyman Tony Seminerio.
</P>
<P>
   Seminerio, who has ruffled party feathers before by endorsing
non-Democrats, did not give specific reasons for endorsing Lazio
but said he did it ''wholeheartedly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican candidate also went to Commack, Long Island where
volunteers began handing out the first of 1 million pieces of
campaign flyers and newsletters to be distributed statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Mayor Rudolph Giuliani also did not attend the
parade, although a bevy of Democratic officials looking to fill his
job next year were there. They included City Council Speaker Peter
Vallone, Bronx Borough President Fernando Ferrer, City Controller
Alan Hevesi, and Public Advocate Mark Green.
</P>
<P>
   State Comptroller H. Carl McCall, who has expressed interest in
running for governor on the Democratic ticket, was also on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton later attended a post-parade union barbecue on the Upper
East Side.
</P>
<P>
   Parade organizers moved the parade to the weekend after Labor
Day after failing to spark interest from marchers or spectators.
</P>
<P>
   But in this presidential election year, thousands of marchers
turned out and the public crowd was the largest in recent years,
although their numbers still hovered in the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   The largest concentration of spectators was only two deep around
St. Patrick's Cathedral where Clinton, marching with Malloy and
AFL-CIO National President John Sweeney, stopped to greet
Archbishop Edward Egan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're here to support the working men and women,'' Egan told
Clinton. ''It's not about politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what we're here for, too,'' she responded.
</P>
<P>
   Some along the parade route didn't have a clue what they were
watching. ''Who's that? Mrs. Clinton? They're giving her a parade?
How nice,'' said German tourist Myna Leifler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
