<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Habitat For Humanity marks 100th house in Paterson  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PATERSON, N.J. (AP) - Terry Jones and her two children finally
have a home of their own.
</P>
<P>
   All it took was 500 hours of banging nails, attaching siding and
painting walls, as well as the kindness of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' new home was the 100th house built in Paterson by Habitat
For Humanity, the Georgia-based nonprofit group that counts former
President Jimmy Carter among its volunteers. At a rate of 11 new
homes a year, the Paterson chapter is one of the most productive in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Jones brushed back tears as she accepted the keys to her
two-story townhouse on Halpine Street in one of this poor city's
most impoverished neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's tears of joy, because this is what I've always dreamed
of,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones previously lived in a small Paterson apartment with her
children, Imani and Tyree.
</P>
<P>
   ''The space was too small,'' she said. ''There was no room to
move around. The kids needed a backyard to run around and play
in.''
</P>
<P>
   She works for a local bank that works with Habitat For Humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'Why not take a chance and see if I can do this?' ''
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Habitat homeowners get an interest-free mortgage that they have
20 years to repay. They have to do at least 500 hours of ''sweat
equity,'' a euphemism for rolling up their sleeves and helping
build their own house.
</P>
<P>
   In return for the help, they have to meet certain requirements,
such as earning about $23,000 a year and having the ability to
repay the mortgage. Once the mortgage is repaid, the money goes
back into a fund to build other new houses.
</P>
<P>
   The Paterson chapter began working 15 years ago in the city's
Northside neighborhood, an area so bad that a road bridge linking
it with the downtown area had been closed. Crime, drugs and poverty
were rampant.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the neighborhood is still struggling: Liquor stores and
bars dot the corners of many residential streets, and trash still
lines the curbs. Across the street from the construction site, a
row of abandoned, burned-out garages contains tons of trash. The
average income in the neighborhood is about $18,000 a year,
according to Barbara Dunn, the Paterson chapter's executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   But now there is hope, justified by the sight of clean, new
houses that have risen from the rubble of vacant lots and
fire-scarred buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we started here, this was known as the worst neighborhood
in Paterson,'' Dunn said. ''We got most of our property donated
because people just walked away from their lots.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, she said, even Northside land is worth something. Habitat
had to pay $140,000 for the Halpine Street site, where it is
building 16 new homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's an encouraging sign,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Local churches and businesses have been helping. United Parcel
Service funded the entire $66,000 cost of building Jones' home.
</P>
<P>
   Millard Fuller, who founded Habitat For Humanity in 1976 in
Americus, Ga., and recruited Carter in 1984, said the group will
soon dedicate its 100,000th house, one nearing completion in New
York City's Harlem neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   He started the group after a personal crisis led him to question
his values.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a lawyer and a businessman, but my life was falling
apart,'' he said. ''My wife was leaving me and I was hitting the
skids. I ended up in a small religious community outside Americus,
and it was there that we built our first house.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a desire to make my life count for something other than
just piling up money,'' Fuller said. ''Building housing ended up
being what I felt God was calling me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The group has 2,500 chapters worldwide, and is active in 1,569
U.S. cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-09-00 1620 </TRAILER>
