<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 103-year-old Olympian to return flag ''borrowed'' in 1920  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - Hal Prieste grabbed a souvenir after he took
a bronze metal in the 1920 Olympic Games in Antwerp, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 103-year-old Camden man is traveling to Sydney,
Australia, to present the president of the International Olympic
Committee with the Olympic flag he ''borrowed'' after the closing
ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Prieste said he's returning it because ''the Olympic committee
wants it back.''
</P>
<P>
   He left his nursing home with two companions Friday afternoon
and began the 36-hour journey to Sydney, taking along the white
flag bearing five colored Olympic rings.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very pretty with lots of rings in it,'' Prieste told the
Courier-Post of Cherry Hill. ''What good is it doing me (stored) in
a suitcase?''
</P>
<P>
   He was 23 years old when he took third place in platform diving
in the Olympics. To this day, Prieste still regrets that he didn't
perform better.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did three compulsory dives from 16 feet and finished
in last place.
</P>
<P>
   ''Then we went up to 32 feet and they let you do whatever you
wanted,'' he said. ''You could get more points by doing harder
dives. I did the hardest because I wanted to get the most points.
</P>
<P>
   ''I only lost by a couple of points. If I did better on the
compulsory dives, I probably would have won.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking the flag and stuffing it in a suitcase, Prieste
returned to California, where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   He used his fame to grab a silent-movie part as one of the
original Keystone Kops and traveled to Hawaii to perform diving
exhibitions for the Amateur Athletic Union.
</P>
<P>
   In 1932 Prieste formed a traveling comedy show to coincide with
the Summer Olympics in Los Angeles. He later performed his physical
comedy act at dance halls and nightclubs nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never copied off anyone,'' Prieste said. ''I was a creator.
I would make things up and people would laugh and laugh. I had my
name in lights in New York City, on Broadway. 'H. Prieste,' it
said.''
</P>
<P>
   He later took up ice skating and joined a version of the Ice
Follies, which he enjoyed more than diving.
</P>
<P>
   Now he said it's time to give the flag back, and he's happy to
make another trip to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is he the oldest U.S. Olympian, but Linda Nevarez of
the U.S. Olympic Committee's Alumni Relations department said he's
also the oldest Olympic medalist in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will just about finish me up,'' Prieste said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
