<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami to US: Change Behavior  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami,
returning from the U.N. Millennium Summit in New York, said
Saturday that the United States should recognize Iran's new words
and change its behavior toward this Gulf country.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now that the world has accepted that Iran has something new,
fresh and logical to say, the U.S. should recognize it, too,''
Khatami said of efforts he has made since being elected in 1997 to
open Iran to Western nations. He spoke to reporters upon his
arrival at Tehran airport from a weeklong trip to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami was warmly welcomed by dozens of senior Iranian
officials and thousands of youths carrying flowers and pictures of
their president.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
attended Khatami's speech during the summit. But, Khatami said,
''this does not solve the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ''America's behavior should be basically changed. They should
compensate for the problems they have created in the past,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami was not invited to a reception hosted by Clinton later
in the week. The leaders of Iraq, Libya and Cuba were also
excluded.
</P>
<P>
   Ties between Iran and the United States were severed after
Iran's 1979 Islamic revolution, when militants stormed the U.S.
Embassy and kept 52 Americans hostage for 444 days. Iranians resent
U.S. support for the shah, whose regime was toppled in the
revolution, as well as the American role in a 1953 coup that ousted
a nationalist government.
</P>
<P>
   Relations have thawed since the election of the reformist
Khatami, who has sought better relations with Western countries.
The United States has taken some concrete steps in the area of
trade and people-to-people contact, but Khatami said in his U.N.
speech that Iran still had ''serious issues'' with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, Khatami said he met with Algerian
President Abdelaziz Bouteflika on the sidelines of the U.N. summit
and the two agreed to resume full political relations. The
countries suspended relations in the early 1990s after Algeria
accused Iran of aiding Muslim militants.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a very good meeting ... and we announced the resumption
of ties, which had unfortunately been in trouble for many years,''
Khatami said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
