<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huge advertising fight under way to decide control of House  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - In a battle of unprecedented size and
sophistication, Democratic and Republican campaign committees are
lavishing money on television commercials in key races two months
before elections that will determine which party controls the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists in both parties agree that as few as three dozen of
the 435 races around the country will be competitive. A switch of
eight seats would guarantee a Democratic majority next year.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats began airing their ads in July. Republicans, stripped
of their customary election-year financial advantage, started their
campaign only in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Still, both sides are ahead of the spending pace set in previous
campaigns. In addition, virtually all ads are now tailored to the
political landscape in specific districts, a contrast to the
proliferation of ''cookie-cutter'' productions in 1996 and 1998 in
which essentially identical commercials aired in a number of races.
</P>
<P>
   ''The issue advertising this (election) cycle has started
earlier, it will last longer, it's in more places with more depth
than any time'' previously, said Ed Brookover, a former top aide at
the GOP campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Issue ads'' refer to commercials that do not expressly
advocate election or defeat of a candidate and are distinct from
any advertising undertaken by the candidates themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Democrats are paying for a commercial praising Rep. Mike
Forbes, D-N.Y., as a champion of breast cancer research. In
another, they accuse GOP Rep. Ernie Fletcher of Kentucky of voting
''for a budget that raided Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   In a third, they charge GOP Rep. Don Sherwood of Pennsylvania
with voting ''against guaranteed prescription drug coverage for all
seniors under Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have invested in a commercial that lauds Rep. Jay
Dickey in Arkansas as the architect of a plan to provide
prescription drug insurance for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   They also attack Maryanne Connelly, a Democrat running for New
Jersey's 7th District seat, for turning the city of Fanwood, where
she was mayor, ''into Taxwood.'' Connolly is running against
Republican Mike Ferguson for the seat being vacated by Republican
Senate candidate Bob Franks, a district that includes parts of
Union, Somerset, Middlesex and Essex counties.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, where the GOP nomination will not be settled until
October, the party is conducting a political holding action. They
are on the air attacking Democrat Linda Chapin, former chairwoman
of the Orange County Commission, for supporting local tax
increases.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are airing advertisements in roughly a dozen
districts, although Democrats got a jump on the GOP of up to
several weeks in many cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to spend a ton of money'' on issue ads, said Rep.
Tom Davis, R-Va., the chairman of the House GOP campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful about record Democratic fund-raising, Republicans
launched a new effort over the summer to persuade rank-and-file
lawmakers to donate surplus campaign cash or raise funds from
supporters for the GOP advertising effort.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats already have spent millions on ads. With eight weeks
remaining in the campaign, Democratic officials say they are
already closing in on the $6.8 million they spent in all of 1998 on
issue advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to be able to play in all the districts where we
need to, and that's light years ahead of where we were in the last
two (election) cycles'' said Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., chairman
of the House Democratic campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   In a striking display of their financial resources, Democrats
are paying an estimated $1.6 million for a two-week run of a pair
of 15-second ads on television in New York City, one of the
nation's costliest markets. The message is aimed at voters on Long
Island and New Jersey, only a small percentage of the stations'
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats launched their first ad almost two months ago, in a
bid to help Adam Schiff, a state senator, unseat GOP Rep. Jim Rogan
in California. They quickly followed up in a second California
district, targeting GOP Rep. Steve Kuykendall, as well as
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans scoffed that Democrats were spending their money too
early in the campaign to be effective. At the same time, they
attacked some ads as untrue, succeeding in having a few pulled from
television stations, however briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the effect was to send a wave of jitters through the
ranks of vulnerable lawmakers, and, Republicans now concede, to
depress GOP poll numbers in a few places.
</P>
<P>
   The intense use of issue ads by party committees is a relatively
new political phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and the Democrats employed them in the run-up
to the 1996 campaign, attacking Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, the AFL-CIO used them to try and topple the GOP
majority in the House. Republicans responded, at a cost that
officials say was a few million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Republicans spent an estimated $20 million on issue
ads, some relating to legislative issues and some dealing with
Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans and Democrats alike, this year's process is
similar.
</P>
<P>
   Party strategists in Washington use polling data to determine
where the commercials will run and how much to spend. They also
provide direction on the topic involved, according to officials in
both parties. Advertising experts, two for the Democrats and five
for the Republicans, produce the commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, an ad might carry an on-screen disclaimer that says
it was paid for by a state party. In fact, the funds generally are
transferred from the national committee in Washington, the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee or the National
Republican Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The money itself is a blend of hard money, which can be raised
in donations limited in size, and soft money, which can be raised
in unlimited contributions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-09-00 1700 </TRAILER>
