<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, Sept. 9, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
OPEC Nations Support Oil Increase
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- As international pressure mounts on OPEC to pump more
oil to stem surging fuel prices, members of the petroleum producers' cartel said
today they support raising their official output by at least half a million
barrels a day. Oil ministers from Iran and Algeria said they would back an
increase of 500,000 barrels a day -- or 2 percent above OPEC's current
production -- when they meet with their counterparts at a crucial meeting
tomorrow. Saudi Arabian oil minister Ali Naimi went further, suggesting that the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would add ''at least'' that many
fresh barrels to thirsty world markets.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
US Mulls More Colombia Anti-Drug Aid
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House leaders are considering whether to follow up a $1.3
billion aid package designed to help Colombia's military combat the narcotics
trade with $99.5 million more to bolster Colombian police anti-drug efforts. In
negotiations over the original package, which emphasized military aid,
congressional Republicans already switched 14 helicopters and other materiel to
the police. John Feehery, spokesman for House Speaker Dennis Hastert, said today
that Hastert saw a possible need for additional help when he accompanied
President Clinton to Colombia on Aug. 31 for the symbolic delivery of the first
package.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Presses For Wildfire Aid
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton proposed spending about $1.6 billion to
help communities recover from the forest fires that have scorched the West this
summer and to thin millions of acres of federal forests in hopes of preventing
future blazes. A report submitted today to Clinton by two Cabinet secretaries
said the increased removal of trees and brush is needed to reverse almost a
century's worth of firefighting policy that left forests with acres of
undergrowth and ready-to-burn timber.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Presidential Race Tightens
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrat Al Gore has an edge over Republican George W.
Bush in a Newsweek poll of likely voters released today, while a tracking poll
shows a very close race. The race was tight in Illinois and New Hampshire, while
Bush still has a big lead in Texas, according to several new state polls. The
state-by-state battle for electoral votes is crucial because the winning
candidate has to win enough states to collect 270 electoral votes.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Focuses on Funds, Education
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrats Al Gore and Joseph Lieberman will cross Ohio in
matching yellow school buses, pushing a back-to-school campaign message in a
week crowded with television appearances and nearly $10 million in fund raising.
Cincinnati supporters spent today painting signs for what the White House
hopefuls have dubbed their ''On the Road to an A+ Education'' tour on Tuesday
from Wantz Middle School in suburban Dayton to a Middletown high school and,
finally, to Cincinnati State Technical and Community College.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Palestinians Mull Delaying Statehood
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) -- With the peace process in apparent deadlock,
Palestinian lawmakers began a two-day debate Saturday over whether to postpone
their declaration of statehood past next week's fast-approaching deadline. All
signs pointed to a delay, because of intense international pressure on
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat not to disturb the delicate peace talks with a
unilateral move that could provoke conflict with Israel.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton and Barak Meet in New York
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- With Mideast peace talks deadlocked, President Clinton and
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak met today to discuss whether the negotiations
can be salvaged. ''It was really informal. ... It was not terribly
substantive,'' said White House deputy press secretary Jake Siewert, adding that
Clinton wanted to say goodbye to Barak. Both leaders had come to New York for
the U.N. Millennium Summit. Earlier, a senior Israeli official said he had low
expectations of reaching a deal with the Palestinians in the coming weeks and
did not believe that Clinton was bringing new proposals to Barak.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
No. 3 Michigan Defeats Rice 38-7
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Anthony Thomas ran for 131 yards on 14 carries and
scored two first-quarter touchdowns as No. 3 Michigan used a record start to
beat Rice 38-7 today. The Wolverines (2-0) scored 28 points on their first four
possessions, breaking the school record of 24 first-quarter points against
Northwestern in 1991.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Safin, Sampras to Meet at U.S. Open Final
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Marat Safin, who beat Todd Martin 6-3, 7-6 (4), 7-6 (1)
today, will play Pete Sampras at the championship match of the U.S. Open. ''It's
nice to be in the final,'' the 20-year-old Russian said. ''But something is
missing. I want to win.''
AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH KENNEDY 
</P>
