<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man gets five years in prison for killing autistic son  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) - A 73-year-old man has been sentenced to
five years in prison for stabbing his autistic son to death in a
nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   James Joseph Cummings and his wife asked the judge not to send
Cummings to prison, pleading that he took his son's life out of
fear no one would take care of James Jr. after his father no longer
could.
</P>
<P>
   But Superior Court Judge James A. Kennedy said taking a life
must have consequences, no matter what the conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ''He (Cummings) weighed the risks and opted to take his son's
life,'' the judge said. ''But no matter how lofty the motive, this
can't be condoned. The so-called mercy killing has not been
sanctioned by the people of New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, Cummings visited James Jr. in his room at the
Avante nursing home in Red Bank, where the 46-year-old was being
treated after suffering a stroke that left him partly paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Cummings stabbed James Jr. in the chest, walked to a
nursing station to announce what he had done and waited for police
to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   When the nursing home employees went to the son's room, they
found James Jr. had died of a stab wound to the chest. Cummings was
charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Cummings pleaded guilty to manslaughter, and the
prosecution agreed to recommend the minimum sentence of five years
and to dismiss the murder and weapons charges.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, Cummings must serve four years and three
months. The 298 days he has already served in jail will count
toward the prison sentence. Kennedy said he plans to recommend that
Cummings is placed in an institution where he can receive
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   About 12 family members listened in court as Theresa Cummings
described the difficulties of raising a son that doctors wanted
them to put in an institution. She told the judge she didn't
condone what her husband did, but believes he had no control over
his actions.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Cummings' attorney, Mitchell Ansell, said the
family was disappointed and thought he should have been spared a
prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Monmouth County Prosecutor Mark Fliedner said after
the sentencing that his office worked closely with the family to
come up with a just solution.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a devastating family tragedy from every perspective,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-09-00 1707 </TRAILER>
