<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000909.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic Aide: No Vote Observers  </HEADLINE>
By MISHA SAVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The Yugoslav government will not
allow observers from Western countries considered hostile to
President Slobodan Milosevic to monitor elections here, a top
official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection, which comes amid fears of possible vote-rigging
in the Sept. 24 election, is meant ''to protect Yugoslavia's
sovereignty and integrity,'' Information Minister Goran Matic said.
</P>
<P>
   He also blasted government critics who had warned of fraud as
''delegates of American institutions whose aim is to occupy our
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Matic spoke at a news conference at the headquarters of his
neo-communist Yugoslav Left party, a powerful group led by the
president's wife, Mirjana Markovic, and coalition partner with
Milosevic's Socialists.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is running for re-election. His main challenger,
Vojislav Kostunica, who is representing a group of allied
opposition parties, currently leads independent polls by more than
10 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Matic accused the foreign media in Yugoslavia of preparing to
discredit what would be a certain Milosevic victory.
</P>
<P>
   The information minister also accused the Belgrade-based,
non-governmental organization, Center for Free Elections and
Democracy, of being an ''instrument of American agents'' working to
undermine Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the police ransacked the group's premises, also known
by its Serbian-language acronym CESID. They confiscated much of its
equipment, including computers with files.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's ruling coalition had earlier said it will invite a
number of foreign observers of its own choice, mainly from China,
Ukraine, Russia and India.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia now consists of Serbia, Milosevic's power base, and
the much smaller republic of Montenegro, whose separate,
pro-Western government is boycotting the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's supporters in Montenegro say they will organize
voting in the republic, raising further questions of manipulation
in the president's favor.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday evening, the supporters went further. Their leader,
Momir Bulatovic, who also serves as the federal prime minister,
rejected any form of supervision or monitoring by the republic's
government.
</P>
<P>
   Bulatovic's statement, made at a rally near Montenegro's capital
Podgorica, violates a tentative agreement made earlier by
supporters and opponents of Milosevic that the government would
provide polling stations for those who wish to vote on condition of
adequate monitoring to ensure fairness.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rejection of (election) control shows they are preparing
ground for the biggest scam in the recent history of this region,''
said Miodrag Vukovic, a top Montenegrin official. ''Milosevic is
ready to do anything just to avoid losing the elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's supporters in the U.N.-controlled province of Kosovo
were also planning to organize voting facilities there for the
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the harassment of opposition activists continued. The
independent Beta news agency reported Saturday that seven members
of the popular anti-government group Otpor were beaten by the
police in the southern Serbian town of Vladicin Han on Friday after
putting up election posters.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of local opposition supporters chanted against the
authorities during the night, standing in front of the police
precinct where the students were held and demanding their release.
</P>
<P>
   The students were allowed to leave Saturday morning. They
received medical attention later but local doctors declined to sign
reports about their injuries that could be later used in the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the police also seized a transmitter used by a
local, opposition television station in the central Serbian town of
Cacak, in a further crackdown on media not controlled by
Milosevic's central government, Beta said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-09-00 1715 </TRAILER>
