<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe president charged with orchestrating terror in U.S. suit  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Zimbabwe's president, Robert Mugabe, went to a
Harlem church this week to say he would hand his black countrymen
justice - with the return of land stolen under colonialism.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as the 76-year-old African leader entered the Mount
Olivet Baptist Church, he was handed a lawsuit accusing him of
orchestrating political terror, including the beating and fatal
burning of an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed under the Alien Tort Claims Act, a
211-year-old U.S. law originally used against pirates. It allows
foreigners to file civil charges in the United States for alleged
crimes that violate international law.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic, accused of atrocities in
his nation's civil war, was ordered to pay $745 million in damages
by a New York jury under the same law.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe was in New York for the United Nations Millennium Summit
of world leaders when he was served with the civil suit Thursday
charging him with human rights abuses surrounding Zimbabwe's
parliamentary elections in June.
</P>
<P>
   Filed in Manhattan federal court, the suit accuses him of
resorting to violence so his party, the Zimbabwe African National
Union-Patriot Front (ZANU-PF), could stay in power. Human rights
groups have said that Mugabe supporters used brutal tactics against
the opposition Movement for Democratic Change (MDC).
</P>
<P>
   After leading his nation for 20 years, Mugabe is being pressured
to give up power for backing the takeovers of about 1,000
white-owned farms by black people - confrontations in which more
than 30 people were killed. He also faces accusations he looted his
nation's treasury to live in luxury.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking $400 million in damages, plaintiffs in the Manhattan
suit include relatives of people who were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the lawsuit were not available Saturday, but the
New York newspaper Newsday reported that the court complaint cites
the MDC's youth organizer, Tapfuma Chiminya Tachiona, who was
killed in April while campaigning. His widow, Adella Chiminya
Tachiona, allegedly was beaten unconscious with metal bars, boots
and fists by Mugabe's men, then doused with gasoline and set
ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   About two weeks later, MDC candidate Matthew Pfebve was dragged
from his house during an attack by Mugabe supporters, then was
beaten and found naked and mutilated on a road, the court complaint
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another plaintiff, Evelyn Masaiti, also a MDC candidate, says
she was punched, burned by a gasoline bomb and had her house
torched, according to the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   And Maria Del Carmen Stevens, the widow of farmer David Stevens,
charges her husband was kidnapped by ZANU-PF supporters, beaten,
forced to drink diesel oil and fatally shot.
</P>
<P>
   At the Harlem church, Mugabe insisted he does not seek revenge
against opponents. He noted that his nation's last white leader,
Ian Smith, was left to live. ''If I was a vengeful leader, would he
be walking the earth?'' Mugabe asked.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate is considering a bill that would cut off aid to
Zimbabwe, a southern African nation of about 11 million whose
government and ruling party - according to the legislation - are
guilty of ''deliberate and systematic violence, intimidation and
killings.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government has objected to the suit against Mugabe,
citing concerns that he might be entitled to immunity while on a
diplomatic visit. Federal Judge George Daniels then told the
plaintiffs that they had to find their own way to deliver the
papers to Mugabe, Newsday reported.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' attorney, Washington-based Theodore Cooperstein,
did not immediately respond to a message from The Associated Press
on Saturday seeking comment. A message left with the Zimbabwe's
embassy to the United States in Washington was not immediately
returned, and phone calls to the country's mission to the United
Nations went unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   A Secret Service source in New York told the AP that the suit
was handed to the Zimbabwean president by a lawyer from a crowd of
people near the Harlem church, where Mugabe addressed about 4,000
people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-09-00 1752 </TRAILER>
