<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, Sept. 9, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton, Barak Discuss Peace
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- President Clinton met with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
today as the United States signaled determination to salvage Middle East peace
talks despite a grim outlook. Neither side made much of the significance of
their midmorning get-together, at Barak's Central Park hotel in deference to his
observance of the Jewish Sabbath. Before the meeting, an Israeli official said
he expected no new ideas from Clinton on how to revitalize talks with the
Palestinians. After the session, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
characterized it as ''just kind of a friendly meeting.'' Nevertheless, White
House spokesman P.J. Crowley, in New York with Clinton for the United Nations'
Millennium Summit, said despite the lack of progress, the peace process
continues.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
OPEC Nations Back Oil Increase
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- As international pressure mounts on OPEC to pump more
oil to stem surging fuel prices, members of the petroleum producers' cartel said
Saturday they supported raising their official output by at least half a million
barrels a day. Oil ministers from Iran and Algeria said they would back an
increase of 500,000 barrels a day -- or 2 percent above OPEC's current
production -- when they meet with their counterparts at a crucial meeting
Sunday. Saudi Arabian oil minister Ali Naimi went further, suggesting that OPEC
would add ''at least'' that many fresh barrels to thirsty world markets.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Milosevic Aide: No Vote Observers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The Yugoslav government will not allow observers
from Western countries considered hostile to President Slobodan Milosevic to
monitor elections here, a top official said Saturday. The rejection, which comes
amid fears of possible vote-rigging in the Sept. 24 election, is meant ''to
protect Yugoslavia's sovereignty and integrity,'' Information Minister Goran
Matic said. Matic spoke at a news conference at the headquarters of his
neo-communist Yugoslav Left party, a powerful group led by the president's wife,
Mirjana Markovic, and coalition partner with Milosevic's Socialists.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Pushes For Wildfire Aid
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In hopes of preventing future blazes, President Clinton
proposed spending about $1.6 billion to help communities recover from the forest
fires that have scorched the West this summer and to thin millions of acres of
federal forests. A report submitted today to Clinton by two Cabinet secretaries
said the increased removal of trees and brush is needed to reverse almost a
century's worth of firefighting policy that left forests with acres of
undergrowth and ready-to-burn timber.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
2,000 Colombians Protest Drug Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PUERTO ASIS, Colombia (AP) -- About 2,000 people, including schoolchildren
and farmers, protested Saturday against a U.S.-backed anti-drug offensive that
is being planned for this cocaine-producing region. Security forces kept a close
eye on the demonstration in the main plaza of this sweltering Amazonian town.
Many demonstrators said they feel threatened by President Andres Pastrana's
''Plan Colombia,'' which the United States is supporting with $1.3 billion in
mostly military aid and is aimed at eradicating drug trafficking.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Presidential Race Tightens
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a Newsweek poll of likely voters released today,
Democrat Al Gore has an edge over Republican George W. Bush, while a tracking
poll shows a very close race. While Bush still has a big lead in Texas, the race
was tight in Illinois and New Hampshire, according to several new state polls.
The state-by-state battle for electoral votes is crucial because the winning
candidate has to win enough states to collect 270 electoral votes.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sampras To Face Safin in U.S. Open Final
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Teen-ager Lleyton Hewitt let four-time champion Pete Sampras
off the hook in the first set of their semifinal and watched the all-time Grand
Slam record-holder take advantage of it in a 7-6 (7), 6-4, 7-6 (5) victory. That
put No. 4 Sampras in tomorrow's Open championship against No. 6 Marat Safin, who
methodically broke down Todd Martin's game with lobs, drops and passing shots in
a 6-3, 7-6 (4), 7-6 (1) victory.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
BoSox Pitcher Suffers Eye Damage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Red Sox reliever Bryce Florie suffered serious eye damage and
underwent surgery today after being struck in the face by a line drive last
night. He has a severe injury to his right eyeball, but it was not ruptured and
his retina was damaged but not detached, Boston club physician Dr. Bill Morgan
said. The operation was done to release pressure on the eye and assess the
damage. In a statement released by the Red Sox, Morgan said, ''Prognosis for
reasonable vision is guarded.''
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER 
</P>
