<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Newspaper Reinstated  </HEADLINE>
By OMAR SHAMA
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- An Egyptian court ruled Saturday that an
opposition party suspended by the government could resume
publication of its newspaper, but did not rule on the ban on the
party's other activities.
</P>
<P>
   The court said the government's Political Parties Committee,
which suspended the Labor Party and its affiliated Al-Shaab
newspaper in May, does not have the authority to ban a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The court, however, said it did not have the jurisdiction to
rule on whether the suspension of the party itself was valid.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim Shukri, the 83-year-old Labor Party leader, described
the court's decision as historic, saying it showed ''impartiality
in addressing democratic rights. ...This gives us a chance to at
least convey our opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   Shukri played down the significance of the continuation of the
suspension on other party activities. Though Labor Party members
cannot run in upcoming parliamentary elections under the party
banner, they are competing as independents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Islamic party has only two seats in the 454-member
parliament, but its members frequently raise questions
uncomfortable for the government -- such as relations with Israel,
corruption and Islamic values -- in its newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The paper was suspended May 20, nearly two weeks after student
riots against a book denounced in an Al-Shaab article. The protests
left at least 40 students and six policemen injured.
</P>
<P>
   The article described as blasphemous a book by Syrian author
Haider Haider's novel ''Banquet of Seaweed'' that was republished
as part of a government literature promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors accused the newspaper of inciting violence by
allowing Muslim militants to write provocative articles that harmed
the country's ''unity and social peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-09-00 1819 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
