<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plane Lands on Colo. Boulevard  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- A pilot flying a vintage plane to an air show made
an emergency landing on a suburban boulevard Saturday after the
plane's engine stopped. No one was injured.
</P>
<P>
   John Zayac, 41, of Englewood, said the plane developed engine
troubles over the west side of the city after he took off from
Centennial Airport in suburban Arapahoe County en route to the
National Championship Air Races in Reno, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   He turned back, following a major highway to stay away from
residential areas. Then the engine went dead.
</P>
<P>
   The highway Zayac was following had heavy traffic, but he saw
that four-lane Colorado Boulevard south of Denver was mostly clear,
so he maneuvered to avoid a pickup truck and landed on the
boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was more lucky than good,'' Zayac said.
</P>
<P>
   He later took off on the same street and headed for a nearby
airport after the plane's engine was repaired. He was flying a
North American SNJ5, which was used as an advanced trainer by the
U.S. Navy.
</P>
</TEXT>
