<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Striking MoMA workers reach tentative settlement with museum  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The Museum of Modern Art and the union that
represents more than 100 staffers on strike since April reached an
agreement early Saturday, according to the museum and the union
president.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very pleased. We absolutely won on every issue,'' said
Maida Rosenstein, president of the Professional and Administrative
Staff Association - Local 2110 of the United Auto Workers union.
</P>
<P>
   The first strike in 27 years by museum employees - including
archivists, conservators, curators, librarians and other
professionals - forced visitors to pass picket lines, with strikers
at times chanting and blowing whistles.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 a.m. Saturday, the two sides finally reached a deal on a
new contract that will last until the completion in about five
years of the museum's planned $650 million expansion on West 53rd
Street.
</P>
<P>
   The contract was ratified later Saturday by members of Local
2110, which represents 250 of the museum's 630 employees; only
about half actively joined the strike.
</P>
<P>
   The union, one of several representing museum employees, was
fighting what they said were unfair salaries starting at $17,000
for a sales clerk or visitor assistant, with median wages of
$29,000. Another major sticking point was job security during
construction; MoMA had planned for staff reductions.
</P>
<P>
   The old contract expired Oct. 31 and workers in the union went
on strike in April.
</P>
<P>
   The truce reached Saturday provides for an average annual
increase of 3.5 percent, with the contract expiring in five years,
or six months after the new museum opens - whichever is longer,
Rosenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, staffers are guaranteed the right to return
to their jobs after the work is done. Or, a staff member with more
than two years service may choose a severance package of two weeks'
pay for each year of work.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, union negotiators confirmed the status quo on
health benefits, plus an improved dental plan; the museum had
wanted to waive workers' right to bargain over the benefits,
Rosenstein said. Retirement benefits also are better, with employee
contributions matched with various amounts depending on salary and
number of work years.
</P>
<P>
   Staffers also will receive child-care subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   And, the Local 2110 president said, the lowest-paid employees
with many years of experience are to receive seniority-based
increases in addition to the standard raises.
</P>
<P>
   MoMA director Glenn Lowry said that he and the museum's board of
trustees ''believe the contract is fair, balances the needs of our
employees with the museum's budgetary reality, and allows MoMA to
move forward with its entire staff to launch the rich program of
exhibitions and events planned for the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Through Jan. 26, MoMA is exhibiting some of the most-loved
paintings and sculptures from its collection, including such icons
of modern art as Van Gogh's ''Starry Night'' and Picasso's
''Demoiselles D'Avignon.'' Opening Nov. 22 is ''Projects 69,'' New
York artist Julia Jacquette's series of paintings about romance and
desire, with all-American food juxtaposed against erotic images.
</P>
<P>
   MoMA, one of the world's most prestigious art museums, is to
close sometime next year to start the expansion project. During
that time, its major exhibitions will be held in the former
Swingline factory in the Long Island City section of Queens and the
nearby P.S.1 Contemporary Art Center, a converted schoolhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.moma.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-09-00 2028 </TRAILER>
