<HEADLINE> Aussies Urge Racial Harmony  </HEADLINE>
By ROHAN SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Activists planted symbolic hands in a
park here Saturday to urge reconciliation between black and white
Australians, an early protest in a series of demonstrations on the
plight of Aborigines planned for Sydney's Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters said a ''mean-spirited'' federal government is
blocking racial harmony between Australia's earliest inhabitants
and the whites who followed in recent centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Activists placed tens of thousands of colorful plastic cutouts
in the shape of hands on the grounds of Sydney's Centennial Park,
where road cycling events are due to be held during the Sept.
15-Oct. 1 games.
</P>
<P>
   The hand symbol adopted for the demonstration originates with
the Aborigines. For tens of thousands of years, the indigenous
people marked their presence in Australia by pressing smeared hands
against the rock walls of caves.
</P>
<P>
   Street demonstrations are expected during the games, including
plans for a human chain formed by placard-holding activists near
the airport where most visitors and athletes will arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Some 260,000 people signed hand cutouts for the two-day ''Sea of
Hands'' protest, which aims to point out the failures of
conservative Prime Minister John Howard's government on
reconciliation and other Aboriginal issues, said organizers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a mean-spirited prime minister and government in this
country who can't find it in their hearts to say sorry, to accept
the history of this country,'' said Lowitja O'Donohue, an
Aboriginal elder who heads a committee advising the games
organizers on indigenous issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''This sets back the process of reconciliation and sets back the
healing of this country. This country needs healing,'' said
O'Donohue, who is head of the committee that advises the Sydney
games organizers on indigenous issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea of Hands was organized by Australians for
Reconciliation, a group made up of Aborigines and white Australians
</P>
<P>
   Aborigines have lived in Australia for as many as 40,000 years.
After 212 years of white settlement, they are now a minority of
around 380,000 in a population of 19 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Indigenous people are Australia's poorest, least healthy and
most jailed section of society. Their life expectancy is an average
of 20 years less than that of white Australians.
</P>
<P>
   Howard has incensed Aborigines and many white Australians with
his refusal to deliver a formal government apology for past
mistreatment of indigenous people and for policies that have been
criticized as discriminatory by U.N. human rights committees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
