<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haider Chides Leaders on Sanctions  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Far-right politician Joerg Haider claimed
political victory over the leaders of France and Germany in
comments published Saturday, after a European Union panel
recommended lifting sanctions against Austria that the two leaders
had supported.
</P>
<P>
   France's Foreign Ministry said Saturday it had begun consulting
with its EU partners over the panel report on the sanctions, which
were slapped on Austria after Haider's Freedom Party -- criticized
for its anti-immigrant stance -- was brought into the country's
ruling coalition in October.
</P>
<P>
   Haider said the report by the EU's so-called ''three wise men''
vindicated his party and Austria's present government and
represented ''a Waterloo'' for French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
   ''Napoleons always end in Waterloo,'' Haider said in the
interview in an upcoming issue of Austria's Format magazine,
excerpts of which were carried Saturday by the Austria Press
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Haider also said German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder ''played a
very regrettable role,'' in leveling the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ''He believed that when he dirtied Austria's name, he could
distract attention from Germany's historical burden,'' Haider said.
''That shows what sort of personality we are dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   Chirac, whom Haider once ridiculed as a ''pocket-sized
Napoleon,'' has been one of Austria's most vocal critics.
</P>
<P>
   Haider has made statements supportive of some aspects of the
Nazi regime, but has denied pro-Nazi leanings. He has on a number
of occasions offered apologies for the remarks. He stepped down as
head of the Freedom Party, trying to reduce outrage over its
presence in the government.
</P>
<P>
   The EU experts' report concluded that Austria was ''respectful
of common European values'' and that diplomatic sanctions against
Austria had become counterproductive and ought to be eliminated. It
also said the sanctions had strengthened nationalism in Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Under the sanctions, Austria's EU partners broke off bilateral
political contacts, snubbed Austrian ministers attending routine EU
meetings and boycotted school trips, cultural exchanges and
military exercises.
</P>
<P>
   The three experts, former Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari,
former Spanish Foreign Minister Marcelino Oreja and German law
expert Juergen Frowein turned their report over to Chirac, whose
country holds the rotating six-month EU presidency.
</P>
<P>
   French presidential spokeswoman, Catherine Colonna, said France
would study the report and make any decisions in consultation with
the other 13 EU members that applied sanctions Jan. 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-09-00 2115 </TRAILER>
