<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgian royals land in NYC, are greeted in Belgian style  </HEADLINE>
By LUKAS I. ALPERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP)- The prince and princess of Belgium landed in New
York Saturday, and were immediately whisked to a hip downtown
eatery where they were feted in grand Belgian style.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 300 Belgian nationals gathered at Markt, a
cavernous Belgian restaurant, to greet Belgium's crown prince
Phillippe and princess Mathilde, sipping fine Belgian ales and
tossing around innumerable air-kisses.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let us drink to Belgium, particularly with our most honored
representatives with us,'' said Baron Paul De Keersmaeker, chairman
of Belgian brewer Interbrew.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, which was made up of well-to-do Belgian expatriates,
models, and various members of the royal family, applauded as the
royal pair exited their motorcade amid a crush of foreign press.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really wonderful to be living here, and still be able to
meet them,'' said Belgian-born model Annesophie Balsing.
</P>
<P>
   The crown prince and princess are scheduled to embark upon a
five-day, 17-event royal tour of New York to tout all things
Belgian.
</P>
<P>
   That means traveling with an entourage of Belgium's movers and
shakers, including the prime minister, foreign trade officials and
the chairmen of some of the nation's biggest companies.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, Belgium's future king wields power with real
political teeth: The constitutional monarchy appoints each new
government, uniting a linguistic patchwork of Dutch and
French-speakers often at each other's ethnic throats.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the recent health problems of Belgium's 66-year-old
King Albert II, have started tongues wagging that he might yield
the throne to his son.
</P>
<P>
   The pair are scheduled to ring the opening bell of the New York
Stock Exchange on Monday, followed by a series of addresses at the
Fashion Institute of Technology, the Metropolitan Club and the
University Club throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Princess, who has been dubbed by some as the
''Queens of Hearts,'' will also visit a South Bronx halfway house
run by a Belgian nun who is a chaplain at Rikers Island jail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
