<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fox: Mexico's PRI Will Stay Atop  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The Institutional Revolutionary Party will
remain a political force in Mexico, despite losing the presidency
July 2 after 71 years of rule, the party's president said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   During a national forum, titled ''A party discussion: 'What to
do?' Dulce Maria Sauri demanded that the party, known as the PRI,
retain a place in the country's politics because it was the author
of Mexico's democracy, Mexico's government news agency Notimex
reported.
</P>
<P>
   On July 2, Vicente Fox became the first opposition presidential
candidate to defeat a member of the PRI, which has ruled Mexico
since its creation in 1929. The loss left the party in shambles,
with several groups within the PRI fighting for power.
</P>
<P>
   Sauri said the PRI was prepared to monitor the incoming
government. Fox will be sworn in as president on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not leaving, not disappearing,'' Sauri said. ''We are a
political force that knows how to change and participate with
respect to society and politics and democracy in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Sauri stressed that the PRI should continue to debate the
country's problems, as well as its own direction.
</P>
<P>
   Sauri's comments coincided with Fox's announcement Saturday that
he planned to trim Mexico's federal government to make it more
efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with his transition team, Fox said he planned to
organize his government to better respond to the needs of the
Mexican people, Mexico's official news agency reported. He also
said his government would look for ways to cut costs and eliminate
programs and projects that are no longer priorities.
</P>
<P>
   However, he added that he would not begin firing government
workers to cut expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Fox leaves Sunday for a four-day trip to five Central American
countries, starting with Guatemala.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
