<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Stroke Play Record Set  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) -- Jim Wilson fired a record-breaking
8-under 63 Saturday to take the lead after the opening round of
stroke play at the U.S. Mid-Amateur Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, of Chico, Calif., made nine birdies and one bogey to
break the 18-hole Mid-Amateur stroke-play record of 64, set by Tom
Kroll in 1994 and Bert Atkinson in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson birdied the final four holes at the 6,614-yard, par-71
Lower Cascades Course at The Homestead resort.
</P>
<P>
   ''I even missed two or three putts I can't believe I missed,''
Wilson said. ''I really had a shot at birdieing every hole on the
back nine.''
</P>
<P>
   John Poole of Birmingham, Ala., and Keith Decker of
Martinsville, Va., shot 3-under 68s to trail Wilson by five
strokes. Jeff Wilson of Suisun, Calif. and Tony DeLuca of Ashburn,
Va., followed with 2-under 69s. Defending champion Danny Green of
Jackson, Tenn., and 1999 runner-up Jerry Courville of Milford,
Conn., finished at 1-under 70.
</P>
<P>
   Stroke play concludes Sunday. The 264-player field will then be
reduced to 64 for match play, which begins Monday and runs through
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
