<DOCNO> APW20000909.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: China Jails 2 Buddhists  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A Chinese court has sentenced two members of a
Buddhist sect to jail for three years after convicting them under
an anti-cult law China is using to rein in religious and spiritual
groups, a human rights group reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The court in the eastern city of Ningbo accused Liu Yin and Gan
Suqin of being followers of Supreme Master Ching Hai and
proselytizing for her Guan Yin Famen sect, the Hong Kong-based
Information Center for Human Rights and Democracy said.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested in February, the two were convicted and sentenced on
July 18, and having refused to appeal, they were sent to prison,
the group said, citing an officer in Ningbo's Haishu district
court.
</P>
<P>
   The account could not be immediately confirmed. The court was
closed for the weekend, and telephone calls went unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   The communist government over the past 14 months has
aggressively suppressed popular religious and spiritual groups,
seeing them as threats to its power. While the chief target has
been Falun Gong, the biggest and best organized of the groups,
other health and meditation groups have been attacked, as have
Catholic and Protestant churches operating outside state control.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the campaign, the Communist Party-controlled
legislature toughened a law against cults last year, and law
enforcement agencies have increasingly applied it to arrest and
prosecute members of the targeted groups.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, police in central China last month arrested 85
members of an underground Protestant church for using a cult to
undermine the law -- the same charge used against the accused
followers of the Guan Yin Famen sect, the Hong Kong group reported.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Master Ching Hai is a Buddhist nun with a shadowy past
and a chain of restaurants and business ventures from Australia to
the United States. Believed to be from Vietnam, she has a broad
following in Taiwan and in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The Information Center said her group began winning converts in
China in 1992 and now has 500,000 followers across 21 provinces and
major cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-09-00 2215 </TRAILER>
