<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, Sept. 9, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
OPEC Nations Back Oil Increase
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- As pressure mounts on OPEC to pump more oil to stem
surging fuel prices, members of the petroleum producers' cartel said Saturday
they support raising their official output by at least half a million barrels a
day. Oil ministers from Iran and Algeria said they would support an increase of
500,000 barrels a day -- or 2 percent above OPEC's current production -- when
they meet with their counterparts at a crucial meeting Sunday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: China Jails 2 Buddhists
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A Chinese court has sentenced two members of a Buddhist sect
to jail for three years after convicting them under an anti-cult law China is
using to rein in religious and spiritual groups, a human rights group reported
Saturday. The court in the eastern city of Ningbo accused Liu Yin and Gan Suqin
of being followers of Supreme Master Ching Hai and proselytizing for her Guan
Yin Famen sect, the Hong Kong-based Information Center for Human Rights and
Democracy said. Arrested in February, the two were convicted and sentenced on
July 18, and having refused to appeal, they were sent to prison, the group said,
citing an officer in Ningbo's Haishu district court.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
French Truckers Lifting Blockades
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French truckers began eliminating nationwide blockades at oil
refineries and fuel depots Saturday once union leaders unanimously ended a
six-day protest that caused havoc at airports and gas stations. With most of
France's gas stations still dry, however, the removal of blockades was not
expected to ease immediately the struggle faced by motorists who've been waiting
in line to fill their tanks. The Interior Ministry said 30 oil refineries and
fuel depots were still blocked as of Saturday evening, compared with more than
100 earlier in the day.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Haider Chides Leaders on Sanctions
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Far-right politician Joerg Haider claimed political
victory over the leaders of France and Germany in comments published Saturday,
after a European Union panel recommended lifting sanctions against Austria that
the two leaders had supported. France's Foreign Ministry said Saturday it had
begun consulting with its EU partners over the panel report on the sanctions,
which were slapped on Austria after Haider's Freedom Party -- criticized for its
anti-immigrant stance -- was brought into the country's ruling coalition in
October. Haider said the report by the EU's so-called ''three wise men''
vindicated his party and Austria's present government and represented ''a
Waterloo'' for French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton, Barak Meet After Summit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- President Clinton and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak met today to see if the Middle East peace negotiations could be salvaged,
as more than 150 world leaders headed home from the U.N. Millennium Summit. Most
of the top-level dignitaries left New York, armed with a challenge by
Secretary-General Kofi Annan to use their power to give billions of people a
better life in the 21st century. But a few leaders, like Barak and Clinton, kept
up the diplomatic whirl, which included a meeting today between Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and Pakistan leader Pervez Musharraf at the
Waldorf-Astoria hotel.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
'Big Brother' Members Mull Walkout
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Rebellion was afoot today in the ''Big Brother'' house.
The reality show's six remaining contestants threatened to march out of the
camera-filled house in which they've been sequestered since July, forgoing their
shot at the $500,000 prize. ''Some things in life are more important than
money,'' one contestant said. The plot to walk out on Wednesday's upcoming live
show, when the next housemate was scheduled to be ousted, was made public on the
CBS show's companion Webcast on Saturday. Some players expressed doubt that all
would follow through on the pact.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Williams Wins U.S. Open Title
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Two months after beating Lindsay Davenport at Wimbledon for
her first Grand Slam title, Venus Williams confirmed her place as the best in
the game, if not in the rankings, by beating Davenport again 6-4, 7-5 in the
hardest-hitting women's final in U.S. Open history. On the men's side, Pete
Sampras beat Lleyton Hewitt in a 7-6 (7), 6-4, 7-6 (5) victory. That put No. 4
Sampras in tomorrow's championship against No. 6 Marat Safin.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yankees Beat Red Sox 5-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Scott Brosius hit a three-run homer in the seventh inning,
leading the Yankees to a 5-3 win over the Red Sox today and an eight-game lead
over second-place Boston in the AL East. Jose Canseco hit a two-run homer in the
ninth off Red Sox reliever Tim Wakefield. It was Canseco's 14th home run of the
season and 445th of his career.
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER 
</P>
</TEXT>
