<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Enters Budget Battle  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM C. MANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican Sen. John McCain, recruited by GOP
leaders for their budget fight with the White House, asked
Americans to vote out any lawmaker who would undermine the nation's
surplus with wasteful spending.
</P>
<P>
   The former presidential hopeful expressed suspicions that both
parties might share guilt by the time this year's budget is
enacted. He had especially harsh words for President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton does not want compromise, the Arizona senator said
Saturday in the GOP's weekly radio address, and will do anything to
defeat Congress in the annual battle, even at the cost of renewed
budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president is a charming fellow, and a heck of a
salesman,'' McCain said. ''But I wouldn't buy a used car from him
if I were you.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the government shutdowns of the mid-1990s, which
generally were blamed on the Republicans who run Congress, gave
Democrats an excuse to fault the GOP for any budget impasse. That
left the president a free hand to push through more spending, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Such rhetoric is what Republican leaders had in mind when they
talked McCain into taking a more visible role in the GOP budget
campaign, exploiting broad voter appeal McCain exhibited in the
Republican primaries.
</P>
<P>
   When he signed on to the campaign Thursday, however, McCain
warned that he planned to target anybody who tried to lard the
budget with pork-barrel projects or other unwarranted spending.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's talk, McCain kept his maverick image intact by
laying into Republican big spenders who push through bills
benefiting their own states or districts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sorry to say that in past years some of us have bargained
our way out of these annual budget battles by surrendering our
principles and joining the president in a no-holds-barred race to
the pork barrel, figuring that if we can't lick him, we might as
well join him,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won't support a bill that risks our future for short-term
political gains, whether Democrats or Republicans are
responsible,'' he said. ''If in a few weeks, administration and
congressional negotiators emerge from a smoke-filled room carrying
another huge, pork-barrel spending bill, I'll vote against it, and
I'll ask you to vote against it too, on Nov. 7, Election Day.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Joel Johnson said the
administration agrees ''that Congress always loads these bills up
with pork-barrel spending. We also agree with Sen. McCain that the
Republican economic plan leaves nothing for Medicare and nothing
for Social Security and would keep us from paying off the debt.
</P>
<P>
   ''However,'' Johnson said, ''the president intends to stand firm
on the priorities he's outlined: putting more cops on the street,
more teachers in the classroom, modernizing our schools and adding
a prescription drug benefit to Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has earned a reputation for speaking his mind, especially
about the campaign finance system, tobacco and defense spending. In
the process, he has crossed his party's leaders, including Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   For example, McCain has criticized Lott for securing $1.5
billion for an amphibious assault ship that the Navy never
requested to be built in Lott's hometown of Pascagoula.
</P>
<P>
   Lott endorsed Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the eventual nominee,
over McCain in the GOP presidential race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-09-00 2308 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000909.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missing sheriff's candidate back after three-week disappearance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MACCLENNY, Fla. (AP) - The candidate for Baker County sheriff
missing for three weeks - including returned home Saturday, raising
suspicions that he may have staged his own disappearance as a
political move.
</P>
<P>
   Agents from the Florida Department of Law Enforcement had been
searching for Julian Pendleton since he was reported missing Aug.
19 after he was seen heading to a candidate's forum. His pickup
truck was found near his home, its door ajar, the keys in the
ignition and his cell phone was on the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Pendleton declined to comment after leaving the sheriff's office
where he was questioned for four hours or return telephone calls to
The Florida Times Union.
</P>
<P>
   His sister, Julie Burnham told the newspaper that Pendleton left
town because he felt he was being harassed by deputies from
incumbent Sheriff Joey Dobson's office.
</P>
<P>
   Pendleton was issued a traffic citation and received a warning
several weeks ago for being disorderly at a grocery store. Deputies
also caught him dumping 50 pounds of sugar in a park, supposedly to
draw ants to disrupt Dobson's campaign kickoff cookout, which was
set for the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Dobson called the harassment claim ridiculous and said
Pendleton's disappearance had a political motive.
</P>
<P>
   ''From the beginning, we thought this was a hoax,'' said Dobson,
who is seeking his second term. He will face Pendleton, the sole
Republican in last Tuesday's primary, in the November general
election. Dobson won the Democratic primary Tuesday with 68 percent
of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nickmeyer, FDLE supervisor of special agents, said Pendleton
told agents he had been in New Jersey for the past three weeks.
Nickmeyer said it is unlikely charges of intentionally perpetrating
a hoax would be filed against Pendleton.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thing we set out to do was to make sure he got back safe
and sound. He is, and we feel we have done our job,'' Nickmeyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's Detective Lt. Chuck Brannan said Pendleton told
investigators he had been staying in New Jersey with a cousin,
James Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Brannan said the pair returned to northeast Florida each of the
past three weekends, with Woods dropping Pendleton at a motel
outside Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Woods could not immediately be reached for comment late
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Brannan said investigators were still trying to determine
whether Woods was compelled to report Pendleton's whereabouts to
police since he knew Pendleton had been reported missing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-09-00 2310 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000909.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smith: Camara Will Stay at Ky.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Kentucky basketball coach Tubby Smith said
Saturday that junior forward Jules Camara decided to stay at the
school.
</P>
<P>
   Camara, arrested last weekend on a drunken driving charge,
pleaded innocent Friday. His former high school coach, Oak Hill
Academy's Steve Smith, said earlier in the week that Camara was
leaning toward transferring from Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   But the university issued a statement Saturday night, saying
Tubby Smith hoped to end speculation surrounding Camara.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have spoken with Jules on numerous occasions over the past
week -- as has my staff and our athletics director Larry Ivy -- and
Jules has decided to remain a Kentucky Wildcat,'' Smith said in the
statement. ''We are very pleased with his decision and look forward
to him rejoining our team in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Camara, a 6-foot-11 junior forward who was expected to start for
the Wildcats next season, was arrested early last Sunday and
charged with driving under the influence. Kentucky's no-tolerance
alcohol policy mandated that Camara be suspended indefinitely,
pending the outcome of his legal proceedings. A conviction would
cost him his scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Tubby Smith, who is in Australia with the U.S. Olympic
team, nor Ivy would comment further due to the pending legal case,
the university said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-09-00 2332 </TRAILER>
