<DOCNO> APW20000909.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Head Is Left Waiting for a Ride  </HEADLINE>
By ROB GLOSTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Juan Antonio Samaranch was left
stranded at his hotel. But, hey, no one expected the Olympic
transportation system to work without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials celebrated a smooth trial run by trains and
buses Saturday during an opening ceremony dress rehearsal. And they
apologized for the gaffe in which the IOC president was forced to
wait at his hotel for a bus.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Roads and Transport Authority reported no major
problems as 81,000 commuters traveled by public transportation to
the Olympic Stadium for the first of two dress rehearsals for the
opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ORTA spokesman Paul Willoughby said 81,000 people were
transported to and from the stadium, with 57,000 traveling by train
and 24,000 by bus.
</P>
<P>
   The only problems related to the dress rehearsal had nothing to
do with transportation -- fireworks capping the ceremony started
three grass fires, and a large sheet bearing the Olympic logo
shredded in a segment near the show's finale.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, though, transport officials were embarrassed
by a mixup that forced the International Olympic Committee's top
officials to cancel a tour.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch and other members of the IOC's executive board waited
20 minutes for a bus provided by Sydney Olympic organizers that was
supposed to take them to the International Broadcast Center for a
tour.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were waiting for 20 to 25 minutes,'' Samaranch said Sunday
as he toured the Olympic Village. ''They said, 'Ten more minutes.'
It was not possible. I had something to do. I had a very important
meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   The head of the transportation agency went to the IOC's hotel to
apologize to Samaranch, and a contrite Olympics minister Michael
Knight called him from Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   Willoughby said a misunderstanding resulted in the bus going to
the wrong pickup location -- the headquarters of the Sydney Olympic
organizing committee instead of the IOC's hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was not a transport problem, it was a question of
dispatching,'' IOC spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a little bit upset he could not go to the IBC, but he
understood the situation,'' Servan-Schreiber said. ''He is very
confident that ORTA can make it work for the games.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch denied a Sydney newspaper report that described him as
''furious.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I was not angry. It was very easy to explain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the latest transportation problem confronting Sydney
Olympic officials, who have said for weeks their greatest concern
about the games is whether the transportation system can cope with
Olympic crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch and other IOC executive board members traveled -- by
bus -- to their Olympic Village tour Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bus was waiting this morning,'' Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
   Bus problems in the Olympic Village already have led to fears of
a repeat of the 1996 Atlanta Games, which were plagued by
transportation problems, and there have been major difficulties
with a new baggage system at Sydney Airport.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, hundreds of train passengers were stranded for up to
several hours at the Olympic Park station when strong winds knocked
down power lines and knocked out service.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Olympic organizers said they are striving to correct the
transportation problems, and IOC executive board member Jacques
Rogge said Thursday the organizers are simply dealing with
''teething problems'' that can be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not a matter of capacity,'' Rogge said. ''It's a matter
of scheduling.''
</P>
<P>
   Columnist Peter Robinson wrote in The Sun-Herald that the
transportation problems simply are part of the Sydney experience.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Olympics have had one beneficial effect on Sydney life,
it is that they have exposed beyond any shadow of a doubt or any
chance of political obfuscation the disgraceful, ramshackle state
of our public transport system,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ''Things that Sydneysiders have been forced for years to regard
as 'normal' are throwing overseas visitors, including Olympic
teams, into a right old tizzy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Buses and trains which are late or don't arrive. Drivers who
don't know where they are supposed to go and interminable waits for
the next overcrowded vehicle or train. For us locals it is all part
of a rich, continuing tradition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
