<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lee Won't Concede Burris in Del.  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER THORNE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- John Burris, the heavily favored state
House majority leader, narrowly beat retired judge Bill Lee in
Delaware's GOP gubernatorial primary by 44 votes, according to
preliminary totals Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who had conducted a grass-roots campaign and got his name
on the ballot to the surprise of party leaders, refused to concede
the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear to me that there's going to be a recount,'' Lee
told The Associated Press late Saturday. He said he would challenge
the results.
</P>
<P>
   The Delaware Department of Elections reported Burris had 13,887
votes to Lee's 13,843. The tiny Middle Atlantic state has nearly
169,000 registered Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican winner of the GOP primary will face Democratic
Lt. Gov. Ruth Ann Minner in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   An early poll by Mason-Dixon Polling &AMP; Research survey had
Minner with a 20 percentage point margin in separate head-to-head
matchups against both Lee and Burris. Incumbent Democratic Gov. Tom
Carper is running for the U.S. Senate against Sen. Bill Roth, a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   In his victory speech Saturday, Burris said he would take the
primary victory, even with the slim margin. He appealed in his
speech for party unity in the 58 days left before the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   ''Forty votes is a great result,'' Burris said. ''Everybody
knows we have to pull together for November.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary race favored Burris, who was nicknamed the
''Ayatollah'' for his forceful leadership in the House. He was most
recently president of the state Chamber of Commerce, primarily a
lobbying post in a state known for its friendliness to business,
but quit that job so he could campaign full-time.
</P>
<P>
   Burris won the endorsement of state Republicans at their May
convention, and as of Aug. 10 he still had $485,441 left of the
$1.1 million he raised for his campaign. Lee estimated Friday he
had only $55,000 left in his campaign accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Frankly, we thought Bill would have dropped out, especially
after the showing of support I had at the state convention,''
Burris told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who stepped down from state Superior Court last fall after
22 years on the bench, hoped to take advantage of his public
recognition from presiding over the sensational murder trial of
Thomas Capano, a politically connected lawyer convicted of killing
his mistress, who was a secretary for Carper. Capano was sentenced
to death.
</P>
<P>
   Lee put his faith in a grass-roots campaign of more than 1,000
volunteers. Many of his supporters were disenchanted Republicans
getting involved in politics for the first time, or Democrats who
switched parties to support him.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not the money, it's ideas that count,'' Lee said. ''John
has raised four times as much money. We knew we had to run an
efficient campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.state.de.us/election
</P>
<P>
   http://www.leedelaware.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.burrisgovernor2000.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.delawaregop.com
</P>
</TEXT>
